<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1430 GMT, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS -- Former French minister of foreign
affairs Claude Cheysson expressed Saturday his support to the
crack-down on the Islamic militants by the Algerian government.
</P>
<P>
"Face those people there (Islamic militants), there is no other
way possible but counter-violence. You cannot persuade them," said
Cheysson in an interview with the Algerian daily El Watan.
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea has decided to shut down the offices of
military attaches in five countries due to shortage of foreign
currency caused by the current financial crisis, the Defense
Ministry said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The five countries are Venezuela, Greece, Austria, Myanmar and
Morocco.
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- The Los Angeles Police Department (LAPD) is
pushing forward with efforts to place non-violent convicts on a
house arrest program.
</P>
<P>
Police officials in this second largest U.S. city said they are
prepared to send up to 4,000 convicts home with electronic
monitoring bracelets, more than double the current number.
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- Six C-130 military cargo planes dropped about
100 tons of food to herds stranded by heavy snowstorms in eastern
New Mexico, news reaching here said Friday.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Argentine government
Friday reaffirmed its unquestionable sovereignty over Islas
Malvinas (Falklands) and the surrounding waters.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement released on the eve of 165th anniversary
of Britain's occupation of Islas Malvinas (Falklands), the
Argentine government said it is determined to regain its
sovereignty through peaceful negotiations in accordance with the
Constitution and international demands.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuela and Chile have signed a trade agreement to
lift all customs tariffs beginning in 1998 in an effort to promote
bilateral trades.
</P>
<P>
With the zero tariffs adopted on January 1 of this year, the
commercial integration between Venezuela and Chile is a reality,
Venezuelan authorities said.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The number of reported murders in Washington
D.C. fell from 397 in 1996 to 301 in 1997, the lowest figure in 10
years, a senior police officer said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news conference, Sonya Proctor, the acting police
chief in the capital of the United States, attributed the drop of
the homicide rate to the strengthened police patrol on city
streets.
</P>
<P>
ROME -- A ship carrying some 300 Kurdish refugees departed from
the Turkish city of Istanbul early on Friday, and will arrive in
Italian waters within three days, the Italian news agency Ansa
reported.
</P>
<P>
The refugees are expected to seek asylum in Italy or Greece,
the agency said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
