<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Free Trade Zone for Central Asia: Kyrgyzstan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 3 (Xinhua) -- President of Kyrgyzstan Askar
Akayev said one of the major tasks facing the Central Asian
Economic Union in 1998 is to set up a free trade zone.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Interfax news agency Saturday, Akayev,
chairman of the union, also reviewed the union's achievements in
1997. He noted the Central-Asia Cooperation Development Bank, a
subordinate of the union, carried out a series of successful
investment projects.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, he added, the union will strive to establish a free
trade zone in order to increase the trade volume by
one to two percent among its member countries.
</P>
<P>
But Akayev cautioned the success of the project will
depend on the will of the region's leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Central Asian Economic Union, set up in 1994, grouping
Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Uzbekistan, aims to strengthen
cooperation in culture, science, technology, economy and trade
within the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
