<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Minister Cancels Visit to Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- British Minister of State at the
Foreign and Commonwealth Office Tony Lioyd has canceled his
planned visit to Zambia due to the house arrest without charge of
former President Kenneth Kaunda.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Foreign Minister Keli Walubita confirmed here today
that the British minister wants to see Kaunda during his visit.
</P>
<P>
He said it is regrettable that Lioyd has set conditions for
the visit originally scheduled for next week.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian minister called for adhering to the norms of
equality of nations.
</P>
<P>
According to Zambia Daily Mail, Britain has demanded that
Kaunda be charged or released.
</P>
<P>
Lioyd said, "i would want to make it very clear to the Zambian
authority that my trip was planned before Dr Kaunda's arrest but
that I will have to speak directorly with ex-President Kenneth
Kaunda."
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, who was arrested last Thursday in alleged connection
with the October 28 abortive coup, was transferred from prison to
house arrest Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
