<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Cabinet Approves New Economic Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The second phase of Zimbabwe's
economic reform program is set to begin in earnest this year
following the recent approval by cabinet of the blue print
outlining strategies for achieving macro-economic stability.
</P>
<P>
The much-awaited Zimbabwe Program for Economic and Social
Transformation (ZIMPREST) document was drawn up with the
involvement of the private sector, first for the government to
consult with non-policy makers on such a crucial national
document.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Herbert Murerwa said here today the ZIMPREST
document had been accepted by the cabinet during a recent
meeting.
</P>
<P>
''The ZIMPREST has been approved now and later this month, the
document will be discussed at a meeting of the National Economic
Consultative Forum,'' the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The forum comprises representatives of the private and public
sectors and was established along the lines of Malaysia's smart
partnership concept.
</P>
<P>
A successor of the five-year Economic Structural Adjustment
Program (ESAP) concluded in 1995, the ZIMPREST has three key
elements for achieving macro-economic targets.
</P>
<P>
The five-year program seeks a consistent reduction in the
budget deficit to 2.9 percent by the year 2000 from the current
eight percent.
</P>
<P>
A continuous growth in exports is also envisaged and with
sustained improvement investment performance.
</P>
<P>
While ESAP resulted in heavy job losses and social suffering,
the ZIMPREST aims to reduce poverty, create more jobs and
restrict government's role in the economy to merely facilitative
rather than controlling.
</P>
<P>
Murerwa said logistics for the implementation of the program
were still being worked out.
</P>
<P>
The ZIMPREST also seeks to achieve some targets missed by its
predecessor, namely a sustainable Gross Domestic Product (GDP)
growth rate of five percent per annum.
</P>
<P>
Funding for critical balance of payments under the ZIMPREST
has been promised to the tune of one billion Zimbabwe dollars
(about 60 million U.S. Dollars) by the European Union,
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
