<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-03 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan to Observe Turkey-Israel-US War Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Jordan today announced it will
observe the upcoming military exercises in the Mediterranean which
involve navies from Turkey, Israel and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Acting Minister of State for Information Affairs Nasser Lawzi
said after a cabinet meeting today that Jordan made the decision
in response to an official invitation from Turkey to observe the
one-day war game off the coast of Israel on January 7.
</P>
<P>
Jordan hasn't decided on the exact size of the observers'
body and will later announce a list of observers and their ranks,
said Lawzi, who is also minister of public works and housing.
</P>
<P>
The controversial three-way navy drills, which have been put
off twice, sparked harsh criticism from the Arab world because
they were widely believed to target Syria and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Turkey signed two military cooperation agreements with Israel
in 1996, which annoyed its Arab neighbors. Egypt, Syria and Iraq
are spearheading an Arab campaign against the growing military
alliance between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Jordan was the only country in the region to be invited by
Turkey to send observers to the exercises, and was under pressure
from its Arab brothers not to do so.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish leadership has time and again explained that the
war game involving five ships, a number of helicopters and search
planes, was "merely rescue and search exercises...for humanitarian
purposes only." But the Arabs seemed not convinced.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed peace with Israel in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, Israel and Turkey are all beneficiaries of U.S. aids in
recent years and are believed to be firm allies of the U.S., which
endeavors to secure its vital economic interests in the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
