<HEADLINE> Top UK Companies Outperform Smaller Ones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 3 (Xinhua) - The largest 100 British companies
significantly outperformed medium-sized groups last year, said a
survey by FTSE International and the Frank Russell group of
consultants.
</P>
<P>
The survey released here today was established to chart the
performance of FTSE 100 and FTSE 250 companies according to two
classifications: value stocks with a low share price to book
value, and growth stocks.
</P>
<P>
The research said the average difference in total returns
achieved by the 100 largest companies in the growth category and
their medium-sized counterparts was 20 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
In the year as a whole, the 100 biggest growth companies
returned almost 29 percent while the 250 medium-sized companies
returned 8.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the value category the 100 largest companies returned 28
percent and the medium-sized companies 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
Kenneth Ayers, an adviser to the Frank Russell company, said:
"The purpose of the indices is to provide an appropriate measure
for investors to judge those managers."
</P>
<P>
The figures highlight the difference between large and
medium-sized companies. The study showed that value beat growth in
the lower performing medium-sized sector by 2.7 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
