<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moi's Victory to Be Declared Soon: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The victory of incumbent
President Daniel arap Moi, who has garnered more than enough
votes for returning to power, will be declared "very soon", an
official with the Electoral Commission (EC) told Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
A swearing-in ceremony will come as soon as the EC announces
the final results, which will happen "at any time from now but
most likely on Sunday or Monday," said the official.
</P>
<P>
As the counting draws to an end, Moi is heading the poll with
half a million votes more than his closest challenger, Democratic
Party's Mwai Kibaki and has got more than 25 percent of the votes
in five out of the country's eight provinces, meeting all
requirements by law for a qualified head of state.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, EC Chairman Samuel Kivuitu said despite chaos
and delays caused by bad weather and technical problems on
Election Day (Monday), "the exercise was executed successfully"
with "no breach of the law."
</P>
<P>
The polling had to be extended and ended on Tuesday due to a
late start, and, as the results of Moi's possible win, two
leading opposition parties had asked for a re-run, saying the
voting was rigged.
</P>
<P>
In response, the EC said the poll should be accepted because
it was carried out peacefully with high turn-out and the fact
that "there are no percentages of voters who have been denied a
chance to cast the votes."
</P>
<P>
"It is noted that (the turn-out of voters) in the majority of
the constituencies recorded between 65 percent and 85 percent,"
much higher than the level in the last elections five years ago,
said Kivuitu.
</P>
<P>
Among 151 out of 210 constituencies in the country where the
counting wound up, Baringo North in Moi's power base Rift Valley
Province saw the highest turnout with 96.40 percent and Kisauni
the lowest, which also hit 42.78 percent, up from 1992's 40.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
A total of 9,031,141 registered Kenyan voters were expected to
to elect one president, 210 parliamentary members and 2,955 local
councillors for the next five years starting from 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
