<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Provision in Kenyan Laws to Repeat Elections: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Kenya African
National Union (KANU) today said there was no provision in the
Kenyan laws for the Opposition to direct the Electoral Commission
to conduct a repeat election.
</P>
<P>
This was said by an official of KANU headquarters at a press
conference today in response to the demand by two opposition
parties to repeat the 1997 General Election.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Democratic Party (DP) and National Development
Party (NDP) yesterday rejected the provisional results of the
General Election and demanded a repeat of the presidential
election within 21 days.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, DP presidential candidate Mwai Kibaki and his
counterpart Raila Odinga of NDP said that incumbent President
Daniel arap Moi had "desperately manipulated" the Electoral
Commission to rig the election in his favor.
</P>
<P>
The KANU official said the allegations made by the two
opposition leaders that KANU has been involved in manipulation of
the elections "have no basis at all".
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the intentions of such charge against KANU
was designed to "cover up their own malpractices in the elections
process including their violence proned behavior".
</P>
<P>
Senior KANU official Bonaya Godana told the press conference
that it was Kibaki who had "made elections rigging his pet topic"
since the process of counting votes began in various parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Kibaki's supporters violently blocked KANU
agents from entering into polling and counting centers to perform
their duties in Nakuru, Naivasha, Molo, Subukia, Mathioya and
Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Kibaki's agents in Siakago, South Mugirango and Mwala were
arrested with presidential ballot papers "all marked in favor of
Mr. Kibaki", he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper of East African Standard today reported
that opposition party Safina yesterday accepted the outcome of
the just ended General Election, saying that it was nonsensical
to seek nullification of the polls.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Ford-Kenya also reportedly said yesterday that it
was so far satisfied with the provisional results of the General
Election which had been officially announced by the Electoral
Commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
