<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Titanium Smeltery to Set up in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 3 (Xinhua) -- A titanium smeltery will be set
up in the port city of Nacala, northern Nampula Province of
Mozambique in the next three years, the Mozambique Information
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to cost 500 million U.S. Dollars and
heavy sand, the raw material needed, will come from neighboring
Muebase Mines, Zambezia Province, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Jose Kamaphane, who is responsible for the project, revealed
that the project was proposed by Gencor, a South African company,
and a British company Billiton and has got support from the
Mozambican government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
