<HEADLINE> Egypt's Trade Minister to Visit India Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Minister of Trade and
Supply Ahmed Gowaili is due in New Delhi on Monday on a week-long
visit to India to boost bilateral trade ties, the Middle East News
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian minister will attend an international conference
on trade, investment and technology scheduled for January 8-10 in
the Indian capital.
</P>
<P>
Gowaili today told reporters his visit to India is within the
framework of Indian-Egyptian cooperation in economic, trade and
industrial domains, adding that he will brief the Indian officials
on Egypt's experience in investment.
</P>
<P>
Gowaili said he will have talks with his Indian counterpart on
ways of broadening trade between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian delegation will particularly focus its attention
on the Indian experience in small-scale projects, cotton trade
and textiles, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian delegation consists of representatives from the
Egyptian Federation of Industries, Chamber of Commerce and 20
other businessmen.
</P>
<P>
The trade and investment conference, to be inaugurated by
Indian Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral, will be attended by
representatives from major European and Asian economic blocs.
</P>
<P>
Gujral visited Egypt last October and held talks with Egyptian
leaders on shoring up cooperation in the fields of agriculture,
food security, biotechnology, energy, information, water
resources, computer programming and setting up joint industrial
ventures.
</P>
<P>
During his two-day visit, the two countries signed three
agreements on cooperation in tourism, customs and culture.
Preparations are under way to stage an Indian products exhibition
in Cairo in April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
