<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Poll Acceptable: Independent Observers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The second multi-party poll in
Kenya was conducted basically free and fair and its results
should be accepted by all Kenyans, three main independent
observer organizations said today.
</P>
<P>
Although the final results are yet to come in, it is fully
clear that incumbent President Daniel arap Moi will be the winner
by taking an assailable lead in total votes collected and
reaching standards under law for a qualified president.
</P>
<P>
The "results do on the whole reflect the wishes of the Kenyan
voters and should be accepted in total," said the Institute for
Education in Democracy, the Catholic Justice and Peace Commission
and the National Council of Churches of Kenya in a document
issued jointly today.
</P>
<P>
The eight-page document was based on reports from 840 campaign
and nomination process monitors and 28,126 poll observers the
three bodies jointly sent out across this eastern African country
on Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The voting process was generally handled well by polling
station officials, and closely scrutinized by party agents and
poll watchers," it commented.
</P>
<P>
"The vote count, while quite chaotic and slow," said the
document, "was also closely scrutinized by party agents and
observers, and appears to have been largely carried out
satisfactorily."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Democratic Party (DP) and National Development Party
(NDP), two most prominent opposition parties in Kenya, said they
would reject Moi's win, asking a repeat of the poll which they
accused of being rigged with general chaos and delays.
</P>
<P>
But they failed to reveal their further plans, if they had
any, in case of Moi's swearing-in, which is said to come as soon
as the official results is announced.
</P>
<P>
In response to the threat voiced by DP and NDP to reject the
polling results, the government has warned that the police would
"deal swiftly and firmly" with anyone who tried to disturb the
peace.
</P>
<P>
Latest results showed that so far Moi has garnered over 2.2
million votes, half a million more than his closest challenger,
DP Chairman Mwai Kibaki. NDP's leader Raila Odinga takes the
third place far behind.
</P>
<P>
Moi, 73 and taking power sine 1978, has also managed 73
percent of the vote in Rift Valley and North Eastern provinces,
46 percent in Western Province, 42.3 percent in Coast, 41 percent
in Eastern and 26 Percent in Nyanza. Only Nairobi and Central
Province continue to elude Moi.
</P>
<P>
Under Kenya's current constitution, the candidate who wins the
highest total and no less than 25 percent of the votes in at
least five of Kenya's eight provinces can be qualified as a
president.
</P>
<P>
So far Kibaki has received 1.7 million votes countrywide and
has managed 25 percent of the vote only in three provinces --
Nairobi (44 percent), Central (89 percent) and Eastern (26
percent).
</P>
<P>
While, Moi's ruling Kenya African National Union (KANU) has
won 102 parliamentary seats, followed by DP with 35 seats.
</P>
<P>
The Electoral Commission (EC) said today it could not announce
the official results unless vote counting is finished in all
constituencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
