<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Food Supply Situation Under Assessment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) and the World Food Program (WFP) plan to
assess Tanzania's food supply situation in the 1997/98 crop
season.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by FAO here today said that the assessment
is aimed at evaluating the prospect for this year's long rains
season and estimating the imports requirement, including food
aid.
</P>
<P>
The FAO will also assist the Ministry of Agriculture and
co-operatives in developing a credible intervention strategy for
future drought mitigation in the east African country, according
to the statement.
</P>
<P>
In a recent meeting with FAO's new representative in Tanzania,
Sulayman Sait M'boob, Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye expressed
appreciation of the international organization's assistance to
the country, especially in food production.
</P>
<P>
More than 1.4 million people are facing food shortage after a
severe drought hit Tanzania last year.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the FAO provided Tanzania with emergency assistance
fund totaling 2.65 million U.S. Dollars for drought relief and
livestock disease control.
</P>
<P>
Food situation in Tanzania, with a population of 30 million,
may become worse after devastating floods starting from last
December swept most parts of the country. Meterological
departments predicted that the above average seasonal rains
linked to El Nino weather phenomenon will last till April.
</P>
</TEXT>
