<HEADLINE> Mordachai on Israeli Withdrawal from South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordachai has said Israeli troops can withdraw from Lebanon after
an interim security arrangement is in place, Lebanon's Orient
Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the radio, Mordachai told the Lebanese magazine
Arab Nation that Israeli government is ready to implement the
United Nations Resolution 425 which demands Israeli unconditional
withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to reach an interim security agreement with
Lebanon under the support of Syria although it isn't put in the
framework of comprehensive peace accord," Mordachai said, quoted
by magazine in its latest issue.
</P>
<P>
The interim agreement he proposed will be able to put an end to
the circles of violence in south Lebanon and mark a positive step
toward building up trust and overcoming obstacles in the course of
reviving negotiations between Israel and Syria and Lebanon, he
added.
</P>
<P>
But the radio did not say when and in what circumstances the
Israeli defense minister made the remarks.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 2,000-strong Israeli troops have been occupying a
1,200-square-kilometer tract in south Lebanon since 1985. The
Israeli self-styled security zone was carved with the claimed aim
of preventing its residents in the north from Lebanese guerrillas'
cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
However, the growing casualties of Israeli soldiers in the
area, which last year registered 39 dead and 95 wounded, gave
momentum to the call for an unconditional withdrawal from south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister stressed that the agreement he proposed
should include a halt of military operations against Israel
staged from Lebanese territory and disband of resistance groups.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, he added, the South Lebanese Army,
Israeli militia ally controlling Lebanon's predominantly Christian
town of Jezzine, must be guaranteed to be safe if Israelis exit
and the Lebanese government army should be deployed across the
south.
</P>
<P>
If needed, he said, an international forces can be called in to
take part in the peacekeeping mission in the border area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia's Second City Hit by Fuel Scarcity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia's second largest
town Dire Dawa has been hit by a fuel scarcity since last week,
the Ethiopian News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted residents of the town as complaining that
they have been unable to get fuel from depots since last week,
while the price of kerosine has doubled.
</P>
<P>
The Office of Trade, Transport, Industry and Tourism in the
town administration said it is exerting efforts to transport fuel
by train as the scarcity occurred because of the damage to the
road from the petroleum depot in Djibuoti to Dire Dawa.
</P>
<P>
The road authority is now speeding up the maintenance of the
220-Kilometer Dire Dawa -- Djibuoti road, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
