<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-03 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 18 Nabbed by Turkish Police for Illegal Emigration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Eighteen people were nabbed by
Turkish police today in the Euro-Asian city of Istanbul in a truck
loaded with rubber tires as they attempted to illegally emigrate
to Italy, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Turkish security teams staged a raid and captured these people,
most of them from southeastern Turkey, hidden in the truck that
was about to be loaded onto a ship bound for Italy, according to
the news agency.
</P>
<P>
It said these people claimed they wanted to go to Germany via
Italy in a bid to seek asylum.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Italy traded accusations on Friday over the influx
of Kurdish refugees into southern Italy.
</P>
<P>
Italian Interior Minister Giorgio Napolitano urged Turkey to
prevent further ships leaving Turkey with refugees, according to
the Turkish Daily News today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that Napolitano rejected Ankara's call for Italy
to refuse asylum to Kurdish immigrants and to send them back.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkish Interior Minister Murat Basesgioglu said
that the number of people embarking on the dangerous sea voyages
to European countries has increased as a result of Rome's offer of
asylum to those refugees.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, the Turkish vessel Ararat with 800 Kurdish
refugees on board ran aground near Catanzaro, Italy.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish interior minister said Turkey had taken measures
on its borders and was negotiating with the Italian authorities
to resolve the problem, adding that Turkey was ready to welcome
back Turkish citizens.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that around 2,000 Kurdish refugees had arrived
in Italy's Adriatic coast since September. Italy expatriated about
38,500 illegal immigrants in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
