<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: S. Leone Peace Process Remains in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 3 (Xinhua) -- It seems that the arrival of the
new year will not bring anything favorable to the improvement in
the situation in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Instead, heavy fightings between forces of the military junta
in power and the traditional hunters known as Kamajors continuing
at the turn of the year have further stalled the peace process
scheduled to end this April.
</P>
<P>
The latest fighting between the two sides erupted Friday in a
southeastern town, forcing civilians in the area to flee for
refuge in neighboring Liberia about 20 miles away.
</P>
<P>
The two-hour fighting, coupled with heavy artillery exchanges,
also claimed the lives of several junta soldiers, the British
Broadcasting Corporation reported.
</P>
<P>
It said reinforcements of the Kamajors were seen this
afternoon heading toward another town occupied by the junta
forces, which, according to analysts here, signified that
fighting had escalated in the troubled west African country.
</P>
<P>
The Kamajors started to fight against the junta since the coup
in May last year in an effort to restore ousted president Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Temporary cease-fire was reached after the junta signed a
peace accord with west African countries in Conakry, Guinea five
months following the coup.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, all combatants in Sierra Leone should be
disarmed and demobilized in a process scheduled to begin from
December 1 last year.
</P>
<P>
But the Kamajors refused to put down their weapons, saying
that they were legal civil defense group approved by Kabbah,
while the junta did the same with claims that its troops belonged
to the country's legitimate armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The Revolutionary United Front, which has fought successive
governments since early 1990s and allied with the junta forces in
the wake of the coup, said they were part of the national army
and could not be disarmed.
</P>
<P>
As steps that further breached the Conakry accord, the junta
leader, Johnny Paul Koroma who was on Christmas eve promoted from
the rank of major to lieutenant-colonel, has said the delay of
disarmament and arrival of promised international relief aids
would make it unrealistic to return power to Kabbah on schedule.
</P>
<P>
According to the peace plan, the junta will hand over power to
Kabbah in April this year.
</P>
<P>
Koroma's intention to extend his stay in power got
reinforcements when the junta announced its first budget a few
days ago.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Joe Amaru-Bangali of the junta reportedly
projected revenue at 6.5 billion Leone (about 7.1 million U.S.
Dollars based on price in early 1996).
</P>
<P>
But he admitted that only one billion Leone could be realized
due to the economic sanctions imposed by west African countries
and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions had caused shortage of consumer goods, including
food items and fuel, which, the minister decried, has
"aggravated" the cost of living in the country, although the
junta was still importing some goods.
</P>
<P>
As observers are being upset by these happenings with fear
that peace is remote in Sierra Leone, the west African
peace-keeping force known as ECOMOG has vowed to resolve the
crisis there in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In his new year's message to his soldiers in Monrovia, capital
of Liberia, ECOMOG force commander Major-General Victor Malu told
them to see 1998 as a year to extend final peace and stability in
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG has helped end Liberia's seven-year-old bloody civil
war and created a safe environment for the country's successful
general election to make Charles Taylor the first post-war
president.
</P>
<P>
According to Malu, the achievement of ECOMOG in Liberia should
be something that can be done in neighboring Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
It appears that Malu's promise partly proves the grave concern
of the international community over the deadlocked situation in
that country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
