<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American balloonist Fossett nears Black Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 4 (Xinhua) -- American balloonist Steve
Fossett was over Bulgaria Sunday in his bid to circle the globe
non-stop, and was expected to avoid Libyan airspace despite a
last-minute green light from Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
Fossett had crossed Romania and was flying south along the
western edge of the Black Sea at 1020 GMT, according to a
statement from his team in St. Louis, Missouri.
</P>
<P>
He was traveling at about 40 kilometers per hour at an altitude
of 6,500 meters in clear skies.
</P>
<P>
He was projected to travel east along the southern coast of the
Black Sea and the northern edge of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Fossett left St. Louis on New Year's Eve on his third bid to
make aviation history.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving on this current expedition, Fossett got
permission from 44 countries to enter their airspace.
</P>
<P>
Fossett rode the edge of a polar jet stream over the Atlantic
to attain a top speed of about 220 kilometers an hour at an
altitude higher than 7,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
Another team of US balloonists, Dick Rutan and David Melton,
pushed back their Monday departure from Albuquerque, New Mexico,
by at least 24 hours, their mission officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
