<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Wants to Resume Talks with Syria: Sources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Israel wants to resume peace
negotiations with Syria without preconditions and on the basis of
the U.N. Security Council resolutions 242 and 338, according to
diplomatic sources here today.
</P>
<P>
This was contained in a message from the Israeli government
conveyed to Syrian officials by visiting U.S. Senator Arlen
Specter, who is also chairman of the Security Affairs Committee of
the U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that the Israeli government also showed its
readiness to take into consideration the ideas that the Syrian
side had come to with the previous Israeli government, provided
that such ideas would not be binding.
</P>
<P>
Syria insists that Syrian-Israeli peace negotiations should be
resumed from where they were left off, and Israel should commit
itself to the ideas the two sides agreed to in the previous phases
of negotiations, as well as to the land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. senator held talks Saturday with both Syrian President
Hafez Al-Assad and Foreign Minister Farouq Al-Shara on ways to
restart Syrian-Israeli peace negotiations, which have been stalled
for two years.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Specter also exchanged views with Syrian
officials on a number of current regional issues and ways of
continuing Syrian-U.S. dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Specter reaffirmed the U.S. administration is
committed to pushing forward the Mideast peace march, and it is
intensifying contacts with parties concerned for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
He added that the contacts are designed to enable the peace
initiative made by the U.S. in collaboration with France and a
number of other member states of the European Union acceptable to
all the parties.
</P>
<P>
Syria urged the U.S. today to save the stumbling Middle East
peace process and to change its prejudiced stance in favor of
Israel at the expense of the U.N. resolutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
