<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Urges Further Reforms in Railway Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo
today called on the country's railway industry to accelerate the
pace of reforms.
</P>
<P>
Wu made the call in his letter to a national conference
attended by leading officials from local railway administrations
across China.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, he asked local railway authorities to separate
the functions of the government and railway enterprises, to reduce
the staff to improve the efficiency, to turn from incurring losses
to making profits, and to strengthen the management.
</P>
<P>
According to sources with the Ministry of Railways, the
industry made substantial progress in 1997, when the speed of
trains were raised and a computerized-booking network was put into
operation.
</P>
<P>
The drastical declination of the railway transport volume in the
country was curbed last year.
</P>
<P>
China has planned to have 68,000 kilometers of railways in
operation by the end of 2000, of which, 32 percent are
double-tracked and 24 percent electrified. 
</P>
</TEXT>
