<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's ECIC Raises Contingent Liability for Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Export Credit
Insurance Corporation (ECIC) announced Sunday that it has
increased its contingent liability by more than 30 percent in an
effort to further expand its business capacity and increase its
protection to local exporters.
</P>
<P>
The contingent liability of the ECIC has been increased from
7.5 billion HK dollars (about one billion U.S. dollars) to 10
billion HK dollars (1.28 billion U.S. dollars) with effect from
December 19, 1997, Thomas Yiu, the ECIC Commissioner said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The ECIC Ordinance ruled that the aggregate maximum liability,
the maximum amount which the ECIC is contractually liable to
indemnify its policyholders of all risks if materializing at the
same time, must not exceed its contingent liability.
</P>
<P>
Yiu said that the insured business of the ECIC has maintained a
satisfactory and steady growth over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
"In view of our increased marketing efforts and growing demand
for our services, we see the need to raise the contingent
liability to cope with expected business growth," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the increase in our business capacity
certainly means more exporters will be able to capture more export
orders with the help of our export insurance services," he added.
</P>
<P>
Yiu pointed out that the new contingent liability ceiling is
also aimed at meeting ECIC's strategic plan in diversifying its
business, particularly in developing its Small and Medium
Enterprises Policy and policies for services industries.
</P>
<P>
Also, a higher contingent liability limit will allow the ECIC
to expand to medium-term covers, for example in the export of
capital goods which requires longer terms of credit, should the
demand for such services be established, Yiu said.
</P>
<P>
The ECIC, founded in 1966, is the only credit insurer in Hong
Kong which provides insurance to exporters against the risks of
non-payment for export of goods and services.
</P>
<P>
The ECIC is a government-owned organization with all its
liabilities being guaranteed by the government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
