<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reason Unknown for Power Outage in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Investigators have not found the
exact reason for Saturday's blackout on the entire Luzon, one of
the three main islands of the country, the Philippines News Agency
reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The National Power Corporation (NPC) and the Manila Electric
Company (Meralco) are still "in the dark" and at dispute as to
what has caused the wide blackout that hit Metro Manila and the
whole of the Luzon grid, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Even when both parties have agreed that a Meralco post which
tilted a 115 kv transmission line in Binan, Luguna province,
triggered the outage, questions remain to be answered as to why it
has taken almost 12 hours to restore power in all the affected
areas.
</P>
<P>
The outage started at 1:36 p.m. and NPC officials confirmed it
was fully restored at about 1 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
NPC said the trouble started when the Meralco post hit the 115
kv transmission line, adding that the failure of the circuit
breaker to respond immediately allowed the trouble to cascade,
thereby leading to the automatic tripping of eight power plants.
</P>
<P>
However, Meralco's system operations head Fortunato Leynes said
it was a very small portion of the total system network which
could have been isolated immediately by NPC's circuit breaker.
</P>
<P>
"The upper portion of that particular Meralco post burned due
to still unknown reason, thereby tilting the 115 kv transmission
line it was supporting," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
