<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China Expands Cooperation with ASEAN (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- China and the nine nations in
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) made
substantial progress in developing good-neighborly ties and
friendly cooperation in the political, economic, cultural and
international affairs arenas in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement issued by the People's Republic of China
and ASEAN following the recent Sino-ASEAN informal summit in Kuala
Lumpur has shown that the Sino-ASEAN relations has
entered into a new stage.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement has not only outlined the principles
guiding the relations between the two sides, but also clearly
delineated that the common goal of the two sides is to establish a
good-neighborly partnership of mutual trust geared to the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN, which celebrated its 30th anniversary last August,
consists of nine nations which are neighbors of China. Developing a
good-neighborly partnership with ASEAN based on mutual trust is an
important component of China's foreign policies.
</P>
<P>
Shi Yongming, an associate researcher with the China Institute
of International Studies, said China is a vast country neighboring
with most of the ASEAN nations and it is significant for both
sides to expand the bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have maintained frequent high-level contacts since
China became a consulting partner with ASEAN in 1991. Qian
Qichen, China's foreign minister, has since attended the annual
ASEAN Post-Ministerial Conference (PMC).
</P>
<P>
China became a country in full dialog with ASEAN in July 1996,
opening broad prospects for further cooperation between China and
ASEAN at an even higher level.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have consistently conducted fruitful economic
cooperation, with the bilateral trade volume witnessing an average
annual increase of 20 percent since the late 1980s. The 1996 trade
volume reached 20.4 billion US dollars, and ASEAN has emerged as
China's fifth largest trade partner.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the two sides signed two agreements establishing the
China-ASEAN Joint Committee on Economic and Trade Cooperation and
the China-ASEAN Joint Committee on Science and Technology
Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
They have also supported and coordinated regional and
international organizations such as the Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation and ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF).
</P>
<P>
The first meeting of the China-ASEAN Joint Cooperation
Committee, which was established last February, determined that
the framework of Sino-ASEAN dialog would be formed by five
parallel mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also established the China-ASEAN Cooperation Fund
and approved in principle a number of items such as personnel
contacts, sponsorship of economic and trade cooperation seminars
and informational contacts.
</P>
<P>
Shi noted that the true significance of the joint cooperation
committee is that it has ensured highly organized and systematic
Sino-ASEAN cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The third round of political consultations between senior
officials from China and the ASEAN countries was held in east
China's Anhui province last April. The two sides exhibited their
political will to consider the bilateral ties from a strategic
perspective and to maintain regional peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China Expands Relations with ASEAN (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen attended the fourth ARF
meeting and the meeting between ASEAN countries and its dialog
partners last July.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the latter meeting, Qian said that China and ASEAN
share extensive common interests and have reached a consensus on
various issues. He said the two sides should proceed from a
strategic perspective and develop comprehensive bilateral ties
and improve cooperation.
</P>
<P>
At the 30th anniversary of the founding of ASEAN, Chinese
Premier Li Peng paid official visits to Malaysia and Singapore
last August as guest of their respective prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
Li and the prime ministers of Malaysia and Singapore discussed
the development of good-neighborly friendship and cooperation
geared to the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The recently concluded informal summit between China, Japan,
the Republic of Korea and ASEAN and the August China-ASEAN
Summit were the first top-level meetings between leaders from
East and Southeast Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
The said meetings greatly improved the worldwide
multipolarization process.
</P>
<P>
China and Asean are determined to make the best use of existing
mechanisms for all-round dialogue and cooperation in order to
promote friendship and expand common ground in the following areas:
</P>
<P>
-- placing priority on economic, trade, scientific and
technological cooperation so as to ensure mutual improvement and
common progress;
</P>
<P>
-- coordinating and supporting each other on major regional and
international issues in order to jointly safeguard the legitimate
rights and interests of the developing countries;
</P>
<P>
-- properly handling existing differences or disputes
through friendly consultation in the spirit of seeking common
ground while setting aside differences.
</P>
<P>
China has participated in an extensive aid program under the
framework of the International Monetary Fund, a fact which fully
demonstrates its willingness to help relevant countries overcome
difficulties resulting from the recent financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Though China and some ASEAN members have disputes on the issue
of islands in the South China Sea, they have agreed to solve the
disputes through friendly consultation and negotiation in
accordance with the universally recognized international laws,
including the 1982 UN Convention on the Law of the Sea. The said
agreements were included in the aforementioned joint statement.
</P>
<P>
Shi said that all parties concerned should adopt an approach of
shelving disputes and seeking common development on the issue.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the development of bilateral ties in recent years
has had a positive influence on the world peace and formation of a
new international order.
</P>
<P>
The advancement of bilateral ties in 1997 served as a summary
of relations between China and ASEAN in the wake of the Cold War,
and as a new starting point for the future development of
relations, he said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN currently includes Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Viet Nam.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
