<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Selects Top Ten Research Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- More than 500 Chinese scientists
have selected China's ten biggest scientific results in 1997. The
world's first high-definition DNA "fingerprint" of rice was on the
top of the list.
</P>
<P>
The technology, highlighted by academicians from both the
Chinese Academy of Sciences and the Chinese Academy of
Engineering, has already been used in growing hybrid rice with
better genes.
</P>
<P>
The second one is the damming of the Three Gorges Water Control
Project on the Yangtze River. The designed water flow for the
damming was 14,000 to 19,400 cubic meters per second, and the
deepest water level was 60 meters, both of which rewrote the
world records.
</P>
<P>
The launching of the meteorological satellite Fengyun 2 ranked
third on the list, which also includes two major breakthroughs in
physics -- one concerning the nanometer electronics super-high
density information storage and the other, the expanding of the
diameter of single-crystal silicon.
</P>
<P>
The other successful projects selected are the
13-billion-bytes-per-second super computer, "Yinhe-3", completion
of a mission in the Pacific Ocean for China's 6,000-meter deep sea
robot, the use of cloned antibody in treating the encephalitis B,
the publication of three sets of encyclopedia, containing 140,000
species of plants and animals in China, and the sampling of
large ice cube from the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau by Chinese and
American scientists.
</P>
<P>
The selection of the Chinese top ten research results was
jointly-organized by the Chinese Academy of Sciences, the Chinese
Academy of Engineering and the Chinese Science News.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
