<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Confirms Mordechai's Statement on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu confirmed today that Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai was stating the government's policy when he expressed
Israeli willingness to withdraw from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the confirmation here at this morning's weekly
Cabinet meeting, during which Mordechai's statement was
discussed.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister told the London-based Arabic newspaper
Al-Watan in an interview over the weekend that Israel would accept
the United Nations Security Council Resolution 425 calling for
Israeli pullout from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
But Mordechai conditioned the Israeli pullout on Lebanon's
providing necessary security measures to secure safety of Israel's
northern border.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time that a top Israeli official has
specifically said that Israel would comply with the
U.N. Resolution 425 passed nearly 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai proposed reaching an interim security agreement with
Lebanese government, in which he envisioned an Israeli troop
withdrawal from south Lebanon and its replacement by the Lebanese
Army and possibly international peace keepers.
</P>
<P>
He ruled out a unilateral Israeli pullout if the Lebanese Army
refuses to restores authority in the region.
</P>
<P>
The minister's statement came amid an intensive public debate
over whether Israel should continue its military presence in south
Lebanon, where it is occupying a 15-kilometer-wide security zone
carved out since 1985.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Iranian Hezbollah (Party of God) guerrilla forces have
been fighting a tough war to oust Israeli occupation, which takes
an average death toll of over 30 Israeli soldiers every year.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-nine Israeli soldiers were killed in Lebanon last year,
in addition to the 73 killed in a helicopters collision disaster
near the border early that year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
