<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Forces Withdraw from Southwestern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Reports from Somalia's
southwestern region of Gedo indicate that the Ethiopian forces
have made a total withdrawal from the region.
</P>
<P>
According to Major Mohamed Hussein Abdullahi, a senior
official from the split faction of the Somali National Front
(SNF), the Ethiopian forces have pulled out from the towns of
Lug, Bulo Hawo and Dolow along the border with Ethiopia on
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Abdullahi said the Ethiopian forces have pulled out on their
own accord and withdrew peacefully without firing a single shot.
</P>
<P>
The SNF official who spoke with the reporters here in
Mogadishu today confirmed a meeting that took place between the
Ethiopian force commanders in Dolow and the Rahanwein Resistance
Army militia commanders prior to their withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
"But I don't know the contents of their discussions," he said.
</P>
<P>
A report said more than 500 Ethiopian forces on armed
personnel carriers, tanks and military trailers have made their
rendezvous at the bridge of Dolow-Somalia before crossing to
Dollow-Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian forces from the town of Luq, former headquarters
of Al-Itihad, have been the largest contingent and the latest
that arrived at the rendezvous.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic fundamentalist organization of Al-Itihad also
confirmed the peaceful withdrawal of the Ethiopian forces from
Gedo region which has been occupied since early June last year.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Hassan Dahir Awey, commander of Al-Itihad forces, who
also spoke with the journalists here today in south Mogadishu,
has appealed for peace to the SNF faction of General Omar Haji
Masalle which now controls the region.
</P>
<P>
"Negotiations are the best way for a lasting solution to
Somalia's crises," he said, adding "Al-Itihad is calling for
peace to all parties in Gedo."
</P>
<P>
Abdullahi of SNF also called on his fellow SNF faction and
Al-Itihad men to negotiate to prevent further armed
confrontations in the region. He noted that the withdrawal was
also marked in the towns of Garbaharrey and Bardera in Gedo
region.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian forces have made two incursions into Somalia in
August 1996 and June 1997 in which they captured the three
important towns of Dolow, Bulo Hawo and Luq in their attempt to
the eradicate the presence of the Al-Itihad organization from the
region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reports from the district of Wajid, 90 km northwest
of Baidoa, indicate that the forces of Hussein Mohamed Aidid had
also peacefully withdrawn from the town on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Ali Aden Qalinle, spokesman for the Rahanwein
Resistance Army (RRA), said here that Hussein Aidid's men had
spoken with the RRA commanders in Wajid before pulling out.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Hussein Aidid's men took all their
equipments including the VHF radio communications and battle
wagons.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal of the Ethiopian forces from Gedo and Hussein
Aidid's retreat from Wajid took place at a time when many of
Somalia's faction leaders are in Ethiopia in an effort to cool
down the temper of Ethiopia after the signing of the historic
peace deal in Cairo late last month.
</P>
<P>
Early reports from Addis Ababa indicate that Ethiopia is
finally working towards the implementation of the Cairo agreement
as desired by the Somali people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
