<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moi Declared President Elect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The Electoral Commission (EC)
of Kenya declared this afternoon that incumbent President Daniel
arap Moi has won his final five year term in the just concluded
general elections.
</P>
<P>
The president elect will be sworn in tomorrow morning.
</P>
<P>
"Moi has received the highest number of votes and 25 percent
in five provinces and is thereby declared the winner," Samuel
Kivuitu, chairman of the EC, told a news conference in the Kenyan
capital Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Official results showed that so far Moi has garnered 2.446
million votes (40.12 percent), followed by Democratic Party (DP)
Chairman Mwai Kibaki with 1.896 million votes (31.09 percent).
National Development Party's leader Raila Odinga took the third
place with only 665,725 votes.
</P>
<P>
The 73-year-old Moi who has been in power since 1978, has also
managed to win 69.38 percent of the votes in Rift Valley, 73.08
in North Eastern province, 44.67 in Western Province, 61.05 in
Coast, 35.87 in Eastern, 23.52 in Nyanza, 20.56 in Nairobi and
5.59 in Central Province.
</P>
<P>
Under Kenya's current constitution, the candidate who wins the
highest total and no less than 25 percent of the votes in at
least five of Kenya's eight provinces can be qualified as the
president.
</P>
<P>
Kibaki has managed 25 percent of the votes only in three
provinces -- Nairobi (43.74 percent), Central (88.73 percent) and
Eastern (28.81 percent).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Moi's ruling Kenya African National Union (KANU)
has won 102 parliamentary seats, followed by DP with 35 seats.
</P>
<P>
So far there are nine constituencies whose polling results are
yet to come but they "would not make any differences" of the
final outcome, said Kivuitu.
</P>
<P>
A total of 9,031,141 Kenyans had been registered for the
second multi-party elections to elect one president, 210
parliamentary members and 2,955 local councillors for the next
five years starting from 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: State-Owned Enterprises on the Merger Trail (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- China's reform of the
state-owned sector is on the verge of entering a new phase
featuring more restructuring and enterprise mergers.
</P>
<P>
The new phase will follow in the wake of a merger trend which
swept across the country in 1997, a year featuring the mergers of
some 3,000 enterprises and the reallocation of some 15.5 billion
yuan in state-owned assets.
</P>
<P>
Ren Long, vice-director of the Policies Research Office under
the State Planning Commission, said the widespread inefficiency in
China's economic sector was to a great extent caused by irrational
capital allocations amongst enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese economy, which has experienced rapid growth over
two decades, must improve its efficiency and productivity, rather
than simply expanding the production scale. Therefore, the goal of
restructuring enterprises to ensure the more reasonable delivery
of state-owned capital could be one of the most effective means
for shaping a capital and technology-intensive economy, according
to Ren.
</P>
<P>
She said that steady economic growth in 1997 provided a number
of positive factors, including an ample supply of industrial
products and a buyer's market, rather than a seller's market, a
fact which guaranteed a sound basis for more enterprises mergers
in the country.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the number of enterprises and the volume of
state-owned assets involved, enterprise mergers in 1997 far
exceeded those on previous years.
</P>
<P>
Four large-scale chemical enterprises in Nanjing -- Jinling
Petrochemicals, Yangzi Petrochemicals, Yizheng Chemical Fiber
Co. and Nanjing Chemical Fiber Co. -- merged into a powerful
conglomerate with the encouragement of the central and local
governments. The new venture -- the Donglian Petrochemical Group
-- was formed on November 19, 1997. The restructuring, involving
state-owned assets of 54.2 billion yuan, was the largest in China
since 1949. The Donglian Group is expected to record year-end
figures of 44 billion yuan in sales and 3.3 billion yuan in
profits for 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: State-Owned Enterprises on the Merger Trail (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Qilu Petrochemical Co., another major petrochemical giant,
purchased two chemical plants in Shandong Province, with the
restructuring involving over three billion yuan in state-owned
assets.
</P>
<P>
The country's metallurgical, civil aviation and household
electric appliance industries were also swept by the merger
wave during 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Changhong Group, China's largest color television
manufacturer, acquired two color television ventures, one each in
Jiangsu and Jilin provinces, and purchased the controlling stake
in a battery plant in Mianyang, Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
China General-Purpose Airline Company, a small aviation
company, was mergered with Eastern China Airlines, one of the
major local airlines in China. Three of the nation's largest iron
and steel plants in Hubei Province also announced merger plans in
late November 1997.
</P>
<P>
Local economists acknowledged that the merger wave is far from
reaching its peak. Officials from the Ministry of Machine-Building
Industry noted that the ministry will attempt to form more
productive automotive manufacturing conglomerates by combining the
assets of several of the country's largest automotive plants.
</P>
<P>
They said the merger wave is not only resultant from the rapid
growth of the national economy, but also a timely response to the
global market by domestic enterprises which were overwhelmed by
mergers amongst transnationals in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The only way for Chinese enterprise to compete with foreign
companies is to form a powerful capital scale and create higher
efficiency, according to the economists.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhongyu, minister of the State Economic and Trade
Commission, said that governments at all levels should adhere to
the reform policies of the 15th National Congress of Communist
Party of China which gave green light to forming more enterprises
groups, regardless of boundaries between different regions,
sectors, forms of ownership and countries.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, governments at all levels should use the industrial
policies to guide enterprise mergers, and should extend the
greatest possible efforts to improve both investment conditions
and market order, Wang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
