<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cystic Hyperplasia Increases Suceptibility to Breast Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
discovered that female patients contracting cystic hyperplasia of
the breast have a much more likely chance of developing breast
cancer.
</P>
<P>
Gene research conducted by doctors at the Hebei Medical
University's No.4 Hospital found that the incidence of cystic
hyperplasia amongst female patients suffering from breast cancer
was three to five times higher than that for women free of cancer,
according to today's edition of Health Daily.
</P>
<P>
Geng Cuizhi, director of the research program, said that
pathological research reveals that 20-61 percent of breast
cancer patients also suffer from cystic hyperplasia.
</P>
<P>
She said they also discovered that mammary gland cells change
in form, function, metabolism and degree of differentiation during
their development from normal cells to hyperplasia and
cancer.
</P>
<P>
Researchers noted that cystic hyperplasia is a benign disease,
but caution that doctors should not treat the disease as various
other benign diseases.
</P>
<P>
The researchers suggested that the patients should undergo
tests of gene and cell kinetics to determine if indicators are
normal. However, should indicators show positive, patients should
be treated according to procedures for early stages of breast
cancer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy Postpones Mideast Tour to Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 4 (Xinhua) -- A top Palestinian official said
today that U.S. Mideast peace coordinator Dennis Ross has
postponed his tour of the Middle East till Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Voice of Arabs Radio over phone from
Jerusalem, Mahmoud Abbas, secretary of the Palestinian Liberation
Organization (PLO) Executive Committee, voiced hope that Ross'
mission would help break the deadlock in Israeli-PLO peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
"I hope Ross will direct his efforts to the Israeli side to
implement the redeployment of troops, halt unilateral acts and
promote activities of the sub-committee of the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy's upcoming visit to Israel and the Palestinian
self-rule areas was planned for Monday but was rearranged at
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's request because of a
ongoing budget crisis in his government.
</P>
<P>
As for separate meetings U.S. President Bill Clinton is to hold
with Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat and
Netanyahu in Washington this month, Abbas said the convocation and
success of such meetings depend on the possibility of realizing
progress in outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
"If the negotiations fail, an Arab stance should be adopted
upon which the coming steps will be defined," he added.
</P>
<P>
Ross' trip, including talks with Arafat on Tuesday, follows
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's unsuccessful bid last
month to break a nine-month impasse that started when Israel began
work on a Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem last March.
</P>
<P>
Albright had tried to make Netanyahu produce a blueprint for
Israeli troop withdrawal in the West Bank and Arafat to come up
with a written document on better security cooperation with Israel.
</P>
<P>
But Israel's cabinet has failed to agree on the scope of the
pullback and the extent of "security zones" it wants to establish
in the West Bank in a final peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have been voicing concern that U.S.-sponsored
peace moves, which seem to be gaining steam, could be sidetracked
by Israel's domestic troubles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
