<HEADLINE> Sykora Wins, Tomba Pulls Out in World Cup Slalom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Austria's Thomas Sykora took
his first World Cup victory of the season in an Alpine skiing
slalom on Sunday, while Italian Alberto Tomba pulled out of the
race because of the poor condition on the course in Kranjska Gora,
Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
Reigning overall champion Sykora, who was ninth in the first
leg, timed a combined one minute 37.93 seconds after the two legs
to top the overall standings.
</P>
<P>
Frenchman Pierrick Bourgeat followed on 1:38.09 despite a 19th
place in the opening leg, while Austrian Thomas Stangassinger, the
1994 Olympic champion, third in 1:38.13 from a first-leg eighth
finishing.
</P>
<P>
The broken piste distracted Tomba, who set the best time of the
season, to pull out of the event because officials reversed the
start list of 30 racers instead of the leading 15.
</P>
<P>
Jagge, winner of the first leg, failed to carry on his
impressive performance to finish just 25th overall. 
</P>
