<HEADLINE> Ramos Urges Government-Rebel Peace Talks to Yield </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
has strongly urged the peace panels of the government and the
National Democratic Front (NDF) rebels to forge a comprehensive
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the resumption of formal talks between the
government and the NDF in the Netherlands, Ramos said Sunday that
a "nation united in purpose and fully at peace with itself" will
be one of the best achievements the Filipino people expect in the
centenary of Philippine independence this year.
</P>
<P>
He said negotiations with the NDF have been a "long, difficult,
and protracted quest for peace" that began in an atmosphere of
great expectation in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The people's "expectations and confidence in the talks have
been diminished with every impasse in the talks over the last five
years," he added.
</P>
<P>
The formal negotiations between the two sides have been
recessed four times over the last five years over conflicting
positions on substantive issues.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the often disappointing twists and turns of these
negotiations, the government remains committed to its goal of
attaining a just and lasting peace that the Filipinos want and
deserve," Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
He enjoined the NDF to match the government efforts to break
the current deadlock in the talks and to finally move resolutely
to tackle the substantive issues that could lead to a final peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
In a separate statement, government panel chairman Howard Dee
said the primary objective of the fifth round of peace talks was
for "both sides to arrive at a mutually acceptable agreement on
human rights and international humanitarian law."
</P>
<P>
Dee said that once the agreement is signed, the two panels can
move on to other equally vital substantive agenda of the talks
and, finally, forge a comprehensive peace agreement that the
Filipino people have long prayed and waited for.  
</P>
</TEXT>
