strive for greater consolidation of national unity, maintenance of
stability and enhancement of national development.
</P>
<P>
In his message on the occasion of the country's Golden Jubilee
Independence Day, Than Shwe, Chairman of the State Peace and
Development Council (SPDC), said that "all of us could unitedly
build proper political, economic and social infrastructure with
zeal for emergence of a modern, developed nation."
</P>
<P>
Senior-General Than Shwe's message was read by Major-General
Khin Maung Than, member of the SPDC and Commander of the Yangon
Division at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Than Shwe added that "we are also preserving our culture and
fine traditions so as to revitalize the dynamism of patriotism and
to promote national prestige and safeguard cultural heritage."
</P>
<P>
He warned that "we must be vigilant against various wily
schemes of some neo-colonialists who frequently interfere in the
internal affairs of others," saying that "it is the time when we
must keep constant vigil against any movements of those who want
to disrupt stability and undermine national consolidation finding
fault without any reason on pretext of democracy and human
rights."
</P>
<P>
He also stressed four objectives for observance of the 1998
Golden Jubilee Independence Day which were laid down as "all
citizens to safeguard perpetuation of national independence and
sovereignty, to strive for non-disintegration of the union and
national solidarity, to implement the projects for building a
modern and developed new nation and to endeavor for the emergence
of an enduring state constitution."
</P>
<P>
A flag-hoisting and saluting ceremony was held at the People's
Square here Sunday to mark Myanmar's 50th anniversary of
independence.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, the National League for Democracy (NLD), a
major political party led by Aung San Suu Kyi, also held a
ceremony at the party leader's residence for the observance,
granted by the Myanmar authorities.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar regained independence from the British colonial rule on
January 4, 1948.  
</P>
