<HEADLINE> Four Army Officers Involved in S. Leone Coup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The military government in
Sierra Leone today sacked four of the 17 army officers who
toppled the civilian government of Tejan Kabbah on May 25.
</P>
<P>
A statement on the official radio accused the men of "an act
of sabotage in vandalizing the Iranian embassy (in the west end
of the capital) on New Year's eve and New Year's day."
</P>
<P>
The statement, signed by Colonel Abu Kamara, the under
secretary of defense, said Hassan Bangura, Brima Kamara, Mohamed
Kallon and Foday Kallay as well as Captain Alfred Browne of the
people's army (former rebel combatants), all Corporals who were
people's revolutionary leaders, were also dismissed from the
powerful Supreme Council of State.
</P>
<P>
Corporal Tamba Gboric, a ringleader of the May 25 coup, was
demoted to the rank of Lance Corporal, dismissed from the Supreme
Council of State and stripped of all government vehicles and
security personnel except two and put under probation.
</P>
<P>
Another people's army official, Lt. Colonel Issa Sesay will
lose three months' salary.
</P>
<P>
The statement ordered "all civilians involved in the matter to
surrender all looted items to the nearest police" while the
department of foreign affairs is to send "an immediate apology to
Tehran and all commandeered vehicles returned to the embassy with
immediate effect."
</P>
<P>
Residents around the embassy said soldiers in three trucks
arrived at the embassy close to midnight on December 31 and used
ladders to scale the huge fence and battered steel doors to gain
entrance.
</P>
<P>
"I watched with shock as they carted off computers, furniture
and TVs," one eyewitness said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
The embassy is now being guarded by heavily armed Sierra Leone
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
West African diplomats here said they were surprised over the
government's tough action against the men previously regarded as
"untouchables".
</P>
<P>
"The government is anxious to wipe out its past stains and
deal ruthlessly with any man who wants to derail the revolution,"
one diplomat said. 
