<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Illegal Phone Calls Bounce Back in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian police is worrying
about the return of illegal commercial telephone operators who
have once been driven underground, the Sunday Champion reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The fraudsters resurfaced towards the end of last year by
opening more illegal call offices and expanding their illegal
services from telephone to fax.
</P>
<P>
The illegal call offices offer their services to local, trunk
and overseas callers for amounts much less than the official
prices, costing the Nigeria Telecommunications Ltd. (NITEL)
millions of Naira in revenue, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The fake phone operators, believed to be enjoying assistance
and support of some fraudulent NITEL staff, either tap lines of
big companies with multiple numbers or simply covert a private
line for the "business".
</P>
<P>
The pirated line is often abandoned after millions of Naira
may have been accumulated as bills within weeks.
</P>
<P>
To stem the illegal activities, the government set up a task
force on telecommunications and postal offences in early 1996,
which drove the fraudsters underground following the abolition of
commercial phone services in business centers.
</P>
<P>
Despite regular raids on suspected havens of fraudsters and
arrest of suspects by the task force, the illegal call offices
have continued to boom.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people have been arrested by the task force over
alleged involvement in telecommunication offences nationwide, but
most of the suspects never got convicted or even charged before
properly constituted courts.
</P>
<P>
According to Taiye Shobajo, public relations officer for the
task force, most of those arrested are "miscreants, criminals and
low profile individuals without any home base" or responsible
persons to stand as their guarantors.
</P>
<P>
The officer, however, pleaded the judicial to ensure more
trial and conviction of the suspects in the New Year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
