<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Coach Banned from Swimming Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Germany's swimming team head
coach Winfried Leopold has been banned from attending the world
swimming championships in Perth, the sport's governing body FINA
announced on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
FINA said in a statement that Leopold's accreditation for the
championships starting on Thursday had been revoked and his case
forwarded to its doping panel.
</P>
<P>
Leopold's exclusion came after his stunning admission last week
that he had been involved in doping programs during his time as an
East German coach.
</P>
<P>
"Following the declarations of Mr Winfried Leopold, team leader
of the German Swimming Federation, published by the press and
confirmed by the German Swimming Federation, the FINA Bureau
requested that the executive and several other bureau hear Mr.
Leopold," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"At the close of the hearing, the bureau decided to forward the
case to the doping panel, and withdraw his accreditation that was
granted to him for the eighth FINA swimming world championships."
</P>
<P>
News of Leopold's past emerged last Sunday when German media
reported that Berlin prosecutors had launched a probe into
Leopold's conduct.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutors alleged Leopold provided banned substances to
swimmers between 1986 and 1990 without telling them about, or
sufficiently explaining, the side effects.
</P>
<P>
Four German coaches and two sports doctors were charged earlier
this year with doping offences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
