<HEADLINE> Jagge Steals Leading in Alpine Skiing Slalom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Norway's Finn Christian Jagge
stole the lead from favorite Italy's Alberto Tomba by just one
hundredth of a second in the first leg of a World Cup slalom on
Sunday in Kranjska Gora, Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
Jagge, the Olympic slalom champion in 1992, posted the best
time of 46.93 seconds to add his victory in Sestriere three weeks
ago, where the Norwegian also beat the Italian to fourth.
</P>
<P>
31-year-old Tomba, who set the best slalom time of the season,
complained thoroughly of the piste condition at Podkoren.
</P>
<P>
Local favorite Andrej Miklavc finished third with a time of
47.42 seconds. 
</P>
