<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internal Auditing Helps Supervise Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Internal auditing units set up
by Shanghai's firms and government bodies checked out more than
one billion yuan-worth of losses in 1997, according to the
municipal auditing bureau.
</P>
<P>
The bureau noted that these internal auditing units have helped
supervise the economic activities in this largest city in China.
</P>
<P>
Thirty three cases involving illegally used funds found during
the auditing process have been transferred to judicial organs,
said the bureau.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, some 1,800 internal auditing units had been
set up in the city, employing more than 7,022 auditors.
</P>
<P>
Supervision by auditing has played a positive role in
maintaining China's financial and economic order, said the bureau.
</P>
<P>
Last year, auditors throughout the country saved the state more
than 30 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
During a national conference on auditing last December in
Beijing, Chinese Premier Li Peng called for increased supervision
by auditors across China to check embezzlement and other economic
crimes.
</P>
<P>
The State Auditing Administration is considering working out
regulations on internal auditing to improve the supervision
mechanism.  
</P>
</TEXT>
