<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rapid Economic Development in Chinese Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Beijing witnessed rapid economic
development in 1997, according to a meeting on local economy
opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the city's gross domestic product (GDP)
for 1997 is expected to reach 180.7 billion yuan, an increase of
9.5 percent over the previous year based on comparable prices.
</P>
<P>
According to the meeting, the total investment for fixed assets
stood at 95 billion yuan, up by 8.3 percent; local financial
income reached 20.09 billion yuan, an increase of 25.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The total export and import volume for 1997 is expected to
reach 5.8 billion US dollars, edging up by 4.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The added value produced by industrial enterprises at or above
township level amounted to 54.6 billion yuan, with 56 percent
being realized by state enterprises. High-tech industry became a
driving force for local economic development, with its output
value for 1997 amounting to 21 billion yuan, an increase of 29
percent when counted on comparable prices.
</P>
<P>
The city also scored marked progress in using foreign funds in
1997, with the total volume reaching 2.5 billion US dollars,
rising by 10.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, per capita income for farmers stood at 3,850 yuan,
whereas that for urban residents 7,750 yuan, representing
increases of 5 percent and 7 percent respectively after deducting
prices.
</P>
<P>
The total savings deposit of the city's urban and rural
residents stood at 195.4 billion yuan, up by 17.3 percent over
1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
