<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Pages of Manuscript Ramayana Found in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Two pages of the manuscript of
the Nepali version of the Hindu holy book "Ramayana" have been
found, local newspapers reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Ramayana" was written by Valmiki in Sanskrit about 2,200 years
before. Nepal's pioneer poet Bhanu Bhakta Acharya, born in 1814,
translated it into Nepali.
</P>
<P>
The two pages were found in the house of Bhanu Bhakta's
great-grandson in between the books used to be read by the pioneer
poet.
</P>
<P>
One of the pages has been ravaged by insects, but the other is
intact, the newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
The two pages include the 11th to 22nd and 87th to 98th verses
of the "Ramayana Balkanda", the newspapers said, adding that the
handwriting on both sides of the thick Nepali paper is bold and
beautiful.
</P>
<P>
"I do not know how these pages came to be left here, but I am
sure the writing is in Bhanu Bhakta's own hand," the newspapers
quoted Gopinath Acharya, the youngest great-grandson of the
pioneer poet as saying.
</P>
<P>
He also recalled how his father had on many occasions asked him
to search for the two pages which he had kept in remembrance of
his grandfather.
</P>
<P>
The handwriting is yet to be scientifically identified, and so
far there has been no authoritative identification of the
handwriting in Bhanu Bhakta's "Ramayana", the newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
Two manuscripts of "Ramayana" held separately by the national
archives and by the Bhanu library in Chundi Ramgha, Tanahu
district of western Nepal, the birthplace of the pioneer poet,
have not been identified scientifically either, the newspapers
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
