<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army Command Reshuffled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Major General Mugisha Muntu,
Ugandan army commander, has been replaced by Jeje Odongo, former
state minister for defense in charge of training, local media
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni last night also appointed
Brigadier James Kazini as the acting chief of staff to replace
Brigadier Chefe Ali. Kazini, former commander of the fourth
division, was replaced by Colonel Katumba Wamala, commander of
the second division.
</P>
<P>
The position of state minister for defense is vacant for the
time being.
</P>
<P>
Holding the concurrent post of commander-in-chief of the
Ugandan army, Museveni said in his decree that a further
reorganization in the army command will take place later.
</P>
<P>
Odongo joined the army in 1979 and was trained in Tanzania and
Russia and was regarded as one of the best trained army man in
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Kazini and Wamala belong to the new breed in the army command,
said an army source who did not want to be named. Both of them
are the main figures in the fight against the Lord's Resistance
Army (LRA) in recent years in the northern part of the country
which has resulted in drastic restraining in LRA's rebellion.
</P>
<P>
Both Kazini and Wamala have retained their officer ranks.
</P>
<P>
The new posts for Mugisha Muntu and Chefe Ali are not yet
arranged for the time being. But local media said Muntu is a
ministerial material while Chefe was a possible figure for a
special duty responsible to President Museveni. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
