<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cholera under Control in Zanzibar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar has allowed
several schools to re-open after the outbreak of cholera was put
under control, Sunday News said today.
</P>
<P>
Schools were closed early last month after the epidemic
claimed more than 140 lives on the isles off the east coast of
Tanzanian mainland. Over 600 people have contracted the disease.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a statement from the Ministry of Health as
saying that the decision to open some educational institutions
has been reached following careful consideration of the current
cholera trend and the needs of students at the learning
institutions.
</P>
<P>
The institutions which have been allowed to open doors to
students include senior secondary schools, teacher training
colleges, in-service training centers, the Zanzibar Hotel and
Tourism Training Institute, the Institute of Kiswahili and
Foreign Languages and Islamic institutions for adults.
</P>
<P>
Nursery schools, primary schools and junior secondary schools
will remain closed waiting for further notice.
</P>
<P>
Health officials attributed the spread of the killer disease
to the lack of latrines and waste disposal pits.
</P>
<P>
In another report, the paper said the Ministry of Health
Saturday sent drugs to contain the spread of cholera which has so
far claimed 236 lives in the east-central region of Dodoma.
</P>
<P>
Regional Medical Officer Dr. Meshack Massi said a total of
3,841 people have contracted the disease, and the drugs will meet
the demand for two months, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
He has directed the affected people to rebuild latrines and
stick to basic hygiene regulations.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that 1,984 people on Tanzanian mainland
and 140 others on Zanzibar isles died of cholera last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
