<HEADLINE> China to Invest Heavily in Railway Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Government has
decided to earmark 34.9 billion yuan for construction of railways
in 1998, according to a national railway meeting which opened here
today.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Minister of Railways Fu Zhihuan told the meeting that
China plans to complete track laying for 674 km of new railway
lines and put 821 km of railway lines into operation this year.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, it will also complete track laying for 415 km
of double-track railway lines and will put into operation 385 km
of double-track railway lines and 980 km of electrified railway
lines.
</P>
<P>
Fu said that construction of a trunk railway line in southwest
China will be the focus of this year's railway construction.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Nanning-Kunming Railway Line will be ready for
state assessment; the Baoji-Chengdu, Chengdu-Kunming,
Chongqing-Daxian electrified railway lines will partially be
opened to traffic.
</P>
<P>
The double-track railway line from Liupanshui to Zhuzhou and
preparatory work for construction of Neijiang-Kunming Railway will
be accelerated.
</P>
<P>
He said that key projects, including the Xi'an-Ankang Railway,
the western extension of Turpan-Kashgar Railway Line,
Shuozhou-Huanghua Line, Liupanshui-Baiguo Line, Daxian-Wanxian
Line, as well as a Yangtze River bridge at Wuhu and the
double-track railway line from Handan to Jinan will continue this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
