<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Lifts Power Rationing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 4 (Xinhua) -- With enough water pouring
into major dams, Tanzania has lifted power rationing, Baruany
Luhanga, Tanzania Electrical Supply Company (TANESCO) Managing
Director, has announced.
</P>
<P>
Incessant rains linked to El Nino have filled the Mtera,
Kidatu, Nyumba ya Mungu and Pangani dams with water, making
hydro-electric generators operating in high gear, Luhanga made
the announcement on Friday when addressing his employees at the
head office.
</P>
<P>
By Friday, he said, water levels at the Mtera reservoir in
Iringa Region in the southwest had risen to 695.22 meters above
the sea level, more than five meters higher than the warning
level of 690 meters one month ago, Sunday News reported today.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the company has been able to step up power
generation and put an end to load shedding, which had been in
force for four months last year.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania, whose electricity mainly comes from hydro-electric
power stations, started to introduce power rationing system
following depletion of water at major dams in early September
because of a drought.
</P>
<P>
During the worst period, a number of areas suffered from no
supply of electricity in five days of a week, adversely affecting
industrial production and people's daily life. In late November,
the Zanzibar airport was lost in darkness at night, except for
cruicial sections which were lit by candles and kerosene lamps.
</P>
<P>
With the on-going rains and improved water levels, the TANESCO
managing director expressed optimism that power generation will
be good throughout the year and there will be no need for load
shedding. The company has also sufficient fuel for the running of
generators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's food Deficit Likely to Rise Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's food deficit is
likely to shoot up to four million tons in the current fiscal year
ending June 30, a rise of 81.8 percent as compared with the
previous corresponding year, the Bangladesh Observer said on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The annual food requirement of this South Asian country with a
population of 124.3 million is estimated at 22 million tons.
</P>
<P>
However, the country's total food production this year is
unlikely to exceed 18 million tons, leaving a shortfall of four
million tons, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The daily attributed this to bad weather such as inadequate and
untimely rain and widespread pest attacks.
</P>
<P>
The food deficit should give no cause for unnecessary alarm
among the people, officials said, adding that the government is
preparing a massive import of foodgrain to plug the shortfall, the
daily said.
</P>
<P>
As a related effort, the government has also allowed private
enterprises to import grains, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
