<HEADLINE> China's Railway Transport Halts Decrease in Passengers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- China's railways carried 917
million passengers in 1997, down from 942 million in the
previous year, but halted a sharp decrease in the number of
passengers.
</P>
<P>
Fu Zhihuan, vice minister of railways, made the announcement at
a national railway meeting that opened here today.
</P>
<P>
He noted that operation express passenger trains and
arrive-in-a-night trains, computerized ticket booking, and an
improved railway operational map last year increased the railway
sector's market competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that highways and air transport had seized some of
the railway's market shares. In 1996, the railway passenger
transport volume dropped 12.3 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Railways transported approximately 1.62 billion tons of freight
last year, matching the 1996 level, and earned 84 billion yuan,
8.9 billion more than in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
However, railways contributed greatly to the transport of such
vital goods as cotton, grain, petroleum, and disaster relief
materials, the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
