<HEADLINE> China Reports Good Offshore Oil Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- China expects to double its
present annual offshore oil output to 30 million tons by 2005,
a business executive announced here today.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang Yan, president of the China National Offshore
Oil Corp (CNOOC), the country has offshore oil and gas resources
totaling 24.6 billion tons and 8.4 trillion cu m, respectively.
</P>
<P>
CNOOC has so far verified geological oil and gas reserves
totaling 1.5 billion tons and 320 billion cu m, respectively,
since it was set up in 1982.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, CNOOC pumped a record 16.2 million tons of crude oil
and four billion cu.m of natural gas and has maintained fastest
growth worldwide for a dozen years running.
</P>
<P>
CNOOC recorded an 80 percent success ratio for offshore wildcat
drilling, with additional proven reserves for 1997 standing at 176
million tons of oil and 8.6 billion cu m of gas.
</P>
<P>
CNOOC had signed 131 oil contracts and agreements with 67 oil
companies from 18 countries and regions by the end of 1997, with
foreign investment totaling 6.4 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
CNOOC welcomes foreign cooperation in oil and gas exploration
in the South China Sea, East China Sea and Yellow Sea. It plans to
verify geological oil and gas reserves of 130 million tons and 10
billion cu m, respectively, by the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
