<HEADLINE> 87 Kazakhs Living in Iran Return to Kazakhstan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 4 (Xinhua) -- A group of 87 Kazakhs living in
Iran left for Kazakhstan Saturday, the Iranian newspaper Jomhuri
Islami (Islamic Republic) reported today.
</P>
<P>
It said the Kazakhs returned out of their own will, adding the
volunteer repatriation was arranged upon the demand of the Kazakh
government.
</P>
<P>
They were transferred by a special airliner of Kazakhstan
directly from Iran to western Kazakhstan, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of Kazakhs migrated from the former Soviet Union in
the 1930s following a serious famine in the region, and settled
down in northern Iran.
</P>
<P>
Their repatriation began after the disintegration of the former
Soviet Union and the independence of Kazakhstan in 1991. Before
Saturday, 650 Kazakhs had returned.
</P>
<P>
However, it is not clear how many other Kazakhs are still
living in Iran and whether they also will return to Kazakhstan in
the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
