<HEADLINE> Graffiti Hit Portland Downtown on Weekend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Vandals hit downtown of
Portland, the biggest city in the U.S. northwest state of Oregon,
leaving hundreds of graffiti pieces behind last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Part of the tagging spree was the vandalism of a 85-year
historic library. On walls decorated with historic figures and
benches bearing writers' names was a mess of spray-painted scrawls
left by vandals, local officials said.
</P>
<P>
Every year, the city spends at least 300,000 U.S. dollars to
strip graffiti, which initially appeared in the subways of New
York City in the early 1970s, from public property -- everything
from restrooms to park benches and buses.
</P>
<P>
Across the country, the cost of cleaning up graffiti is
estimated between four and seven billion dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Different measures have been introduced to eliminate the
graffiti. Chicago and Phoenix have banned aerosol spay paint
cans. Other cities require property owners to remove graffiti
within 10 days or face a fine or jail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
