<HEADLINE> China Has 66,000 km of Railway Lines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- By the end of 1997, China had
66,000 kilometers of operational railway mileage, ranking 1st in
Asia, a senior government official announced today.
</P>
<P>
Of the figure, the mileage of electrified railways stands at
nearly 12,000 km, making China the ninth country in the world with
the length of electrified railway lines exceeding 10,000 km,
Vice-Minister of Railways Fu Zhihuan told a national railway
meeting.
</P>
<P>
China invested 34.2 billion yuan in the construction of
railways last year, completing 758 km of new lines, 469 km of
double-track lines, and 1,408 km of electrified railways.
</P>
<P>
A total of 896 km of new railway lines, 551 km of double-track
lines, and 1,916 km of electrified railways went into operation in
1997, Fu said.
</P>
<P>
In the past year, the Beijing-Kowloon Railway passed State
assessment. The Nanning-Kunming Railway became operational ahead
of schedule. Track-laying of the Turpan-Kashgar railway line has
reached Xinhe. Work has started on Xi'an-Ankang Railway.  
</P>
</TEXT>
