<HEADLINE> Airlift Continues for Stranded Herds in N.M. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Another 465 tons of hay were
dropped to herds stranded by fierce snowstorms throughout
southeastern New Mexico Saturday, according to news reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The airlift is a continuation of emergency rescue effort by
six C-130 military cargo planes which dropped 103 tons of food to
ranchers who couldn't reach their livestock.
</P>
<P>
State officials say bad weather killed up to 9,600 cattle and
sheep since Christmas Eve when a series of snowstorms stranded
more than 180,000 herds.
</P>
<P>
Farms around the city of Roswell have been the hardest hit with
ranchers unable to get feed to their livestock.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Department of Agriculture offered 2 million dollars of
disaster aid on Wednesday, agreeing to reimburse ranchers for up
to 30 percent of cost of buying feed to be airlifted in.
</P>
<P>
However, as temperatures warmed late Saturday, some ranchers
canceled their orders for more feed and the five-day rescue effort
finally came to an end. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
