<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Work Begins on Sewage Disposal Plant for Huaihe River Pollution Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Work has started on the
Zhengzhou Sewage Disposal Plant, the largest water pollution
control project along the Huaihe River in eastern China.
</P>
<P>
The plant in this capital of central China's Henan Province
will be built at a total cost of 760 million yuan (91 million US
dollars). Funding will come from a Japanese government loan and
the State Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Construction Li Zhendong came here to attend the
cornerstone-laying ceremony held on the outskirts of Zhengzhou,
where is located on the upper reaches of the Huaihe River, one of
the most polluted rivers in China.
</P>
<P>
After the completion of the first-phase construction, the plant
will be able to dispose of 400,000 tons of sewage daily.
</P>
<P>
So far, nearly one million tons of waste water from the city
are discharged into into the Huaihe River via the Jialu River. To
control the water pollution of the Huaihe River, the province has
started building four sewage disposal plants and will begin
to build another four in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
China now is speeding up the construction of 50 urban sewage
disposal plants along the Huaihe River, which are designed to
dispose of 3.5 million tons of sewage each day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
