<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Mining Industry in Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean mining industry
is facing serious trading problems with earnings in the financial
year ending 1997 going down 11 percent from 484.6 million U.S.
dollars in 1996 to 428.5 million dollars, the Sunday Mail
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Liz Chitiga, chief executive of the Minerals
Marketing Corporation of Zimbabwe (MMCZ), as saying that various
factors including lower prices on the world market and shutdowns
by some local mines had attributed to the shrinking of the
industry.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that the local industry has had
negative growth since management problems in MMCZ were ironed out
in 1992. The industry had since 1992 experienced an upward growth
and there were predictions that some of the minerals,
particularly gold and nickel, could soon match tobacco which is
the country's single largest foreign currency earning commodity.
</P>
<P>
Results for gold which is marketed through the reserve bank
were not available from the Chamber of Mines last week. But like
most minerals, gold also had a bad year with low prices on the
world markets.
</P>
<P>
MMCZ result indicated that the mining industry failed to reach
the target of 5.2 billion Zimbabwe Dollars (about 289 million
U.S. dollars) which it had set for itself. The industry earned
4.8 billion Zimbabwe dollars (267 million dollars) but that much
was realised only because of the heavy devaluation of the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The results also indicated that nickel continued to play a
major role in the mining sector earning 1.4 billion Zimbabwe
Dollars (77.8 million dollars) or more than 25 percent of the
earnings by all minerals. The prices for the mineral were firmer
in the first half of the year but weakened during the last six
months. Sales volumes went up by only two percent.
</P>
<P>
Prices were weak for almost all major minerals including high
carbon ferrochrome, low carbon ferrochrome, ferrosilicon chrome,
asbestos, granite stone, diamonds, emeralds, coal and graphite.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
