<HEADLINE> mee010401hke - Iran Condemns Algerian Massacres </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Iran condemned recent massacres
in Algeria and criticized international human rights bodies for
their indifference towards the ongoing slaughter of innocent
civilians.
</P>
<P>
According to local newspaper Iran News today, Foreign Ministry
spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi said the murders were committed under
very suspicious circumstances which have made the task of
identifying the perpetrators very difficult.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that over 400 people were killed on December 30 by
Muslim militants in the Relizane region, 250 kilometers southwest
of capital Algiers.
</P>
<P>
The massacre at the beginning of the Muslim holy month of
Ramadan was the worst in the past six years since Muslim
insurgency flared up in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said Iran condemns anyone or any group that is
responsible for torturing and killing innocent women and children.
</P>
<P>
He called the human rights organizations' silence over the
massacres "unacceptable," and hoped the initiatives and efforts of
the U.N. chief, the humanitarian organizations and the
Organizations of the Islamic Conference (OIC), the campaign
against genocide could be brought to an end soon.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi noted that the Islamic world should not remain
indifferent to those atrocities, specially in Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
He hoped those responsible for the crimes will be brought to
justice soon and their identities revealed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
