<HEADLINE> 1.7-Billion-Year-Old Cosmic Dust Discovered in Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese geologists have
discovered cosmic dust dating back some 1.7 billion years in
Jixian County of north China's Tianjin City, indicating that a
strong "meteorite shower" hit the area.
</P>
<P>
Experts here said those metal globular grains are of great
importance to research into cosmogony, the formation of the Sun
and space flight.
</P>
<P>
Li Zenghui, a female researcher with the Tianjin Institute of
Geology and Mineral Resources attached to the Ministry of Geology
and Mineral Resources, collected 500 kilograms of dust from quartz
sandstone 859 meters underground in Changgou Village of Jixian
County in the northern part of Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
After scientific sorting, more than 600 milligrams of cosmic
dust were obtained.
</P>
<P>
With advanced facilities, researchers found that the dust
contains black iron globular grains with a diameter of 0.1 to 0.3
millimeters.
</P>
<P>
They believed the comic dust to be around 1.73 billion years
old, which coincides with the geological year of the quartz
sandstone from where the dust was taken.
</P>
<P>
Geologists said Changgou Village is located at the southern
side of Yanshan Mountains, where the geological structures and
large amounts of ancient organisms are well preserved.
</P>
<P>
Chinese geologists also found this kind of cosmic dust in
nearby Luanxian County in Hebei Province, Xingcheng County in
Liaoning Province and Changping County in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
They said the discovery indicates that a strong "meteorite
shower" hit vast areas with Jixian as the center.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
