<HEADLINE> South China's Dongguan Becomes Port of Entry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Dongguan City of south
China's Guangdong Province has become a port of entry which is
open to overseas ships and handles the exit and entry of
travellers by train.
</P>
<P>
Situated at the estuary of the Pearl River, Dongguan is a close
neighbor of Shenzhen, China's first special economic zone.
</P>
<P>
At present, the city has 13,000 overseas-financed enterprises.
Export-oriented businesses of the city now contribute more than 40
percent of the city's gross domestic product (GDP). The city's
annual imports and exports come to 20 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Changping Railway Station of Dongguan became a
first-category railway passenger transport outlet capable of
handling exit and entry of overseas travellers in May 1997, with
the approval of the State Council. It now inspects express trains
from Beijing and Shanghai to Kowloon in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Changping Railway Station, which was renamed as the
Dongguan Railway Station in October 1997, is where the
Beijing-Kowloon Railway Line, Guangzhou-Meizhou-Shantou Railway
Line and Guangzhou-Kowloon Railway Line meet. It has three
substations and is now capable of handling 2.5 million tons of
freight annually and 10,000 passengers daily.
</P>
<P>
Dongguan City's Humen Port, situated on the eastern bank of the
estuary of the Pearl River, opened to foreign ships in June 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
