<DOCNO> XIE19980104.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finland Experiences Abnormal Weather in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Finland experienced multiple
abnormal weather conditions in 1997, with extremes of dog days
rarely seen in a century and a winter season starting as early as
September.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Finnish Meteorological Institute show that
the highest temperature last July hit 31.5 degrees Celsius, a
record over the past 100 years. The average temperature over the
whole summer was much higher than the normal 17 degrees Celsius.
</P>
<P>
There were more than 40 sunny days in the three summer months,
about three times that of normal years, making it the longest
summer season yet since the beginning of meteorological recordings.
</P>
<P>
The other side of the picture is that snow began to fall in
big, feathery flakes in September in the eastern region of Kainuu
and northern Lappi. In other areas, snowfalls came two to three
weeks earlier than usual.
</P>
<P>
The beginning of last year saw a record high of 1.9 meters of
accumulated snow in the outermost north of Kilpisjarvi, which did
not melt away until May.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the abnormal weather, Finland suffered
unbalanced rainfall throughout the year and tornado attacks in the
northwest of the country, which affected crop growth to varying
degrees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
