<HEADLINE> U.S. Condemns Rocket Attack on Baghdad U.N. Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Saturday
condemned a rocket attack on the United Nations Baghdad
headquarters and said it expected a thorough and swift
investigation into the incident.
</P>
<P>
Reports here said that two rocket-propelled grenades were fired
at the headquarters on Friday night but there were no reports of
casualties. No group has claimed responsibility for the attack.
</P>
<P>
"The United States condemns any effort to interfere with the
important work that UNSCOM (the U.N. Special commission) has
undertaken," White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said from Virgin
Islands where President Bill Clinton is taking a New Year's
vacation.
</P>
<P>
"We expect a thorough and swift investigation to determine who
is responsible for the attack," Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Iraqi government also condemned the rocket attack,
saying it was carried out by "hostile parties." A senior Iraqi
official said the incident was under investigation.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq condemned the attack against the U.N. Special Commission
in Baghdad," the Iraqi news agency INA quoted an Iraqi official
spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Such an incident can only be an act of hostile parties who aim
at destroying relations between Iraq and the Special Commission,"
the Iraqi spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The headquarters accommodate the office of the U.N.
humanitarian coordinator in Iraq and the UNSCOM in charge of
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction in an accordance
with U.N. resolutions. 
</P>
