<HEADLINE> Thai-Help-Thai Campaign Gains Momentum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The "Thai-Help-Thai" campaign is
gaining momentum in Thailand as the general public is ready to do
something to help the country out of the current economic crisis,
according to local press reports.
</P>
<P>
The campaign, initiated by a Buddhist monk last month, has been
widely supported by the general public, and prime minister's
office minister Supatra Masdit has been assigned to oversee the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai said Saturday that people in his
hometown of Trang province, southern Thailand, had given him gold
necklaces weighing half a kilogram and some 40,000 baht (850 U.S.
dollars) in cash to help the nation.
</P>
<P>
Last week, an old woman donated 150 grams of gold and 5,000
baht (106 dollars) in cash through the "Thai-Help-Thai" office at
the government house.
</P>
<P>
Yong Wuttikiat, 73, who moved from Hong Kong to Bangkok 30
years ago, donated 600,000 baht (12,800 dollars) to the government
house last week.
</P>
<P>
An unnamed monk has reportedly collected over a million baht
(21,300 dollars) from the public and is expected to turn over the
donations to the government soon.
</P>
<P>
At least 15 temples in the southern province of Chumphon and
various organizations in other provinces are collecting valuables
from the public for the nation.
</P>
<P>
The military also plans a nationwide campaign to collect gold,
jewelry, cash and other valuables from people who are willing to
help the government tackle the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Supatra said that what matters is not how much the government
receives from the people, but the public's goodwill and awareness
of how bad the economic crisis is.  
</P>
</TEXT>
