<HEADLINE> Sino-DPRK Border Market Thriving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Stocks of goods are piled up
in the small wood plate-walled market, covering no more than 200
sq m, and people are busy bargaining, with the help of calculators
and in the only working language of the market -- Korean.
</P>
<P>
This has been a normal scene at the first and only border
shopping-mall between China and the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK), since June 17 last year when the Quanhe-Wonzengri
Border Trading Zone opened on the DPRK side in the DPRK land-port
of Wonzengri.
</P>
<P>
"The opening of the border market is beneficial to the two
sides," said Wang Wenli, Director of the Foreign Trade Bureau of
Hunchun, in the Yanbian Korean Autonomous Prefecture of northeast
China's Jilin province.
</P>
<P>
For the Chinese side, it is helpful for increasing the income
of the border people, he said, noting that it has been a new
source of income for those have been laid off from state-owned
factories in the city.
</P>
<P>
The market opens four days every week, from Tuesday to
Friday. To maintain business order, as too many border residents
want to join in, the number of traders was recently
set. Currently, merely 150 participants from each side are allowed
to operate every trading day, much less than the previous months.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the market has been welcomed by the DPRK side as
it has contributed to easing the shortage of food and daily
necessities in the border area, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
To this day, some 20,000 Chinese visitors, mainly from Hunchun,
have visited the market. Most of them are ethnic Koreans.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that the DPRK authorities do not collect any fee
and levy from the market.
</P>
<P>
While bringing back Chinese-made goods, DPRK businessmen have
supplied sea food to their Chinese counterparts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
