<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan International Reserves $17.3 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan international
reserves were 17.3 billion U.S. dollars at the end of 1997, a 120
million dollar, or 0.69 percent, reduction compared to the
previous week when they were 17.42 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The latest issue of the Weekly Indicators Bulletin published by
the Central Bank of Venezuela (BCV) Saturday shows that the
international reserves indicator has been registering a
contraction since December 8, 1997, due to the Christmas season's
increase of imports and foreign travel.
</P>
<P>
A strong demand for hard currency has made necessary the
constant presence of the BCV, which has had to supply the dollars
to maintain the rate of exchange within the established bands.
</P>
<P>
The drop in the reserves during the last four weeks, according
to the BCV, was 1.53 billion dollars, after the 18.83 billion
dollars were registered up to December 1.
</P>
<P>
However, the reserves at the close of 1997 have surpassed the
level reached in December of 1996 when they were 15.22 billion
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
