<HEADLINE> New Interior Minister Appointed in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo today named Francisco Labastida to replace Emilio
Chuayffet as the Interior Minister.
</P>
<P>
Chuayffet resigned the post on Saturday "for personal reasons."
</P>
<P>
Labastida, the agriculture minister since January 1995 until
Saturday, was born in 1942 in Los Mochis, a city in the
northwestern state of Sinaloa. He is an economist who graduated
from the National Autonomous University of Mexico (UNAM).
</P>
<P>
He was chief of the Social Welfare Department from 1968 to
1972, and from 1972 to 1975 he served as underdirector of Public
Investments in the Presidency Secretariat. From 1976 to 1979 he
was general director of Fiscal Promotion at the Finance and Public
Credit Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Labastida was governor of the state of Sinaloa from 1987 to
1992, and from 1993 to 1994 was Mexico's ambassador to
Portugal. In 1994 and 1995 he was general director of Federal Toll
Roads and Bridges and Connected Services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
