<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Redefines Favorable Policies For Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- A revised Guiding Directory on
Industries Open to Foreign Investment, which went into effect on
January 1st, 1998, allows foreign investors to be exempt from
tariffs and import-related value-added taxes for the projects that
Chinese Government encourages and supports.
</P>
<P>
Vice minister of the State Planning Commission Ye Qing
said that the directory contains 329 items, 270 of which
involve tax exemptions, a sign that China will open wider to the
outside world.
</P>
<P>
The major areas that the state encourages are as follows:
</P>
<P>
-- new agricultural techniques, comprehensive agricultural
development, energy, transport, and major raw materials;
</P>
<P>
-- high and new technology, advanced techniques, and new
equipment and materials which can improve product's functions,
save energy and raw materials, raise economic returns, and meet
market demand, and in whose production capacity China is
insufficient;
</P>
<P>
-- projects that can meet international market demand, upgrade
products, open up new markets, and increase exports;
</P>
<P>
-- new techniques and equipment for comprehensive use of natural
resources and environmental pollution control; and
</P>
<P>
-- projects than can bring into full play the advantages of
central and western China in resource and labor.
</P>
<P>
The State Planning Commission also listed industries, products
and technology projects to which the state gives priority
currently. These cover 29 industries, including agriculture, forestry,
power, machinery, and electronics.
</P>
<P>
The commission will readjust and revise the list every year, in
line with national economic development.
</P>
<P>
The official also elaborated on the guiding principles on
selecting the projects the state encourages.
</P>
<P>
Ye said that the policy readjustment this time is designed to
improve China's economic restructuring and investment structure,
and to create a better environment for foreign investment, in an
effort to maintain sustainable, rapid and healthy economic
growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
