<HEADLINE> No Monarchy, Romanian President Stresses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Romanian President Emil
Constantinescu said Saturday that no attempt to change the
republican system of the country will be allowed during his term
of office.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark in response to a monarchy restoration
attempt by former King Mihai I.
</P>
<P>
Mihai, who returned to Romania on holidays, declared on
December 30, 1997 that he had chosen his eldest daughter as
successor to "all his rights."
</P>
<P>
Political parties and organizations in Romania have reacted
very strongly to the declaration, which they view as a restoration
attempt by Mihai, and urged the president to take a clear stand on
the issue in line with the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
Constantinescu had to suspend his new year holidays on Saturday
and held a special press conference on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Reiterating the government's earlier announcement on the legal
status of the former king, the president stressed that Mihai must
abide by the current constitution and respect the authority of the
government.
</P>
<P>
Mihai was free to return to Romania and live there. As for what
rights he was entitled to, parliament would work out a legal
definition on the matter.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Christian Democratic National Peasants' Party, the
Democratic Party and the National Liberal Party have expressed
their support for the republican political system, saying it best
suits the situation in Romania.
</P>
<P>
Mihai, 76, has been in exile overseas since he gave up his
throne in 1947, but has indicated recently plans to return to live
in Romania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
