<HEADLINE> Major Economic News Briefs From MERCOSUR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from the Southern Common Market (MERCOSUR) in
the past few days:
</P>
<P>
Brazil Unveils 1998 Budget
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil's 1998 budget will be 438 billion dollars, a
six percent cut in investment spending and 15 percent cut in
administrative outlays compared with 1997.
</P>
<P>
Total budget spending is expected to exceed the total income by
13.5 billion dollars, bringing the deficit to more than 1.5
percent of the Gross Domestic Product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian government estimates that the economy would grow
at 1.5 percent to two percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Uruguayan Economy Grows by Six Percent in 1997
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay's economy grew by six percent in 1997.
Official sources revealed that inflation was less than 15 percent
and unemployment 11 percent, while the budget deficit reached 1.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
The industrial and construction sectors registered encouraging
growth. But the most significant result was obtained in tourism,
which attracted more than 2.4 million visitors and earned 750
million dollars, a 150 million dollar increase over 1996.
</P>
<P>
 Argentine Economy Grows by Eight Percent in 1997
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentine Economy Minister Roque Fernandez said
his country's economy grew by eight percent in 1997, surpassing a
government forecast of five percent.
</P>
<P>
Fernandez said the growth will slow down to 5.8 percent in 1998
and unemployment will drop by two percentage points to end at 11.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
Trade Between Argentina, Brazil Increases in 1997
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Trade between Argentina and Brazil reached 14
billion dollars in 1997, a report by the Argentine Industry and
Commerce Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The report, released by the Ministry-led Center of Studies for
Production (CEP), said the average volume in the 1980s was only
1.45 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
