<HEADLINE> 25,000 Families Move into New Homes in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- China's capital completed
apartment buildings with a total floor space of eight million
square meters in 1997, meeting its annual target.
</P>
<P>
Last year the Beijing Municipal Government pulled down
dilapidated houses and build new ones with a total floor space of
1.1 million sq m for 14,000 families.
</P>
<P>
The government also completed the relatively comfortable
housing project with a total floor space of nearly 600,000 sq m,
providing new homes for 11,000 families with less than four sq m
of living space per person.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that Beijing has built over 38 million square
meters of apartment buildings and helped 700,000-odd families
improve their housing conditions since 1991.
</P>
<P>
Beijing urban residents now have an average living space of
13.8 square meters.
</P>
<P>
All families with less than four square meters of living
space per person are expected to move into larger apartments by
the end of this century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
