<HEADLINE> China's Auto Sales Up 6.45 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- About 1.57 million motor
vehicles are estimated to have been sold in China in 1997, up 6.45
percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, car sales are expected to hit 470,000 units, up
20.17 percent from 1996, the "China Daily" Business Weekly
reported today.
</P>
<P>
However, 40 percent of the automobiles were sold to private
buyers, according to a senior official from the Ministry of
the Machine-building Industry (MMBI).
</P>
<P>
Despite the dramatic increase in auto sales, "a
government-encouraged atmosphere favoring car purchase has yet to
arise," Zhang Xiaoyu, director of MMBI's Automotive Department,
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The key to the development of the auto sector lies in
fostering the market," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Business Weekly said analysts expect housing sales to enjoy a
brisk business this year-- a move that may have an impact on auto
purchases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
