<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Opens Strongly in New Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The dollar entered the New Year
with a strong showing against the major world currencies,
reflecting doubts about the Japanese and German economies and
optimism about the United States economy.
</P>
<P>
In New York on Friday, the U.S. currency closed the holiday
week at 132.10 yen and surged to 1,771.91 Italian lire, compared
to the final quotation of 1,759.19 lire on New Year's eve.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that behind the rise of the dollar is the
widespread conviction that ongoing turbulence on the Asian markets
will continue and that the Japanese economy will remain weak in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
The lira has been following the general trend of decline against
the U.S. dollar and showed no reaction to a recent report that
Italy's 1997 budget deficit had been slashed to as low as 2.7
percent of the GDP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
