<HEADLINE> Coal Firms to Be Listed on Stock Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- China will choose 10 to 15 of
its best coal enterprises to issue shares on domestic stock markets
in the next three years, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
As part of an ambitious endeavor to invigorate the lumbering
coal sector, China will first reform four coal producers -- Datong,
Yanzhou, Pingdingshan and Kailuan coal mines -- as enterprise
groups.
</P>
<P>
After a series of trial reforms, the Ministry of the Coal
Industry is ready to restructure all large and medium-sized State
coal mines by the year 2000, Minister Wang Senhao was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
China has about 120 large-and medium-sized State coal firms.
The restructuring is aimed at establishing a clear and stringent
management system to encourage firms to seek more profits and to
protect State assets efficiently.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated China mined 1.33 billion tons of coal in
1997, down 3.2 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
China intentionally reduced coal output last year to give
state-owned firms more room to stem losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
