<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Balloonist Changes Course to Avoid Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Adventurer Steve Fossett
today changed course to avoid Libya on his around-the-world
balloon odyssey and was heading toward the Black Sea.
</P>
<P>
Fossett's Solo Spirit flight team said in St. Louis that
meteorologists guided the balloon to a path off Libya.
</P>
<P>
He could have been forced to abort the flight because he had
still not received permission to fly over the north African
nation.
</P>
<P>
Louis Billones, the team's chief meteorologist, said the balloon
was moving into a wind pattern to avoid Libya by dropping to about
15,000 feet (4,560 meters) over Germany.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Libya granted Fossett permission to fly over, but he
had already used up fuel trying to avoid Libyan airspace and fuel
shortage forced him to land in India.
</P>
<P>
Fossett, on his third attempt to balloon around the globe
without stop, passed through the Netherlands and Germany overnight
and was near Budapest by Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
In the current mission, Fossett is carrying 50 percent more
fuel that is enough to last 20 days.
</P>
<P>
Fossett, a 53-year-old Chicago commodities broker, took off
from St. Louis Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
