<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Citizens in North China Province Taken Good Care of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, January 4 (Xinhua) -- All permanent residents at
or above 60 in north China's Hebei Province will enjoy
preferential treatment when taking buses, visiting public
facilities, seeking legal assistance and many other social
services, according to a notice of the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
Hebei is the first province in the country to pass a regulation
on providing preferential treatment for senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that by the end of 1996, the total number of
local citizens at or above the age of 60 exceeded 7.53 million, or
11.63 percent of the province's total population.
</P>
<P>
According to the notice, senior citizens can enjoy priority in
buying tickets, taking buses and boarding passenger trains, and
they have reserved seats in many public areas.
</P>
<P>
Senior citizens also enjoy a 50 percent discount in buying
tickets to public facilities such as scenic spots, museums, sites
of cultural relics, and performanes at theaters, cultural palaces,
and stadiums.
</P>
<P>
Posts and telecommunications departments at all levels are
urged to give priority to elders when they wish to install
telephones.
</P>
<P>
The province also has regulations on providing priority in
medical treatment to the old people, and gradually improving the
living conditions for old people in elders' apartments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
