<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, January 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI -- The ruling Kenya African National Union (KANU)
Saturday said there was no provision in the Kenyan laws for the
Opposition to direct the Electoral Commission to conduct a repeat
election.
</P>
<P>
This was said by an official of KANU headquarters at a press
conference Saturday in response to the demand by two opposition
parties to repeat the 1997 General Election. (Kenya-Elections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- The second multi-party poll in Kenya was conducted
basically free and fair and its results should be accepted by all
Kenyans, three main independent observer organizations said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Although the final results are yet to come in, it is fully
clear that incumbent President Daniel arap Moi will be the winner
by taking an assailable lead in total votes collected and reaching
standards under law for a qualified president. (Kenya-Election
Results)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordachai has said
Israeli troops can withdraw from Lebanon after an interim security
arrangement is in place, Lebanon's Orient Radio reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to the radio, Mordachai told the Lebanese magazine
Arab Nation that Israeli government is ready to implement the
United Nations Resolution 425 which demands Israeli unconditional
withdrawal from south Lebanon. (Lebanon-Israel)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Eighteen people were nabbed by Turkish police
Saturday in the Euro-Asian city of Istanbul in a truck loaded with
rubber tires as they attempted to illegally emigrate to Italy, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Turkish security teams staged a raid and captured these people,
most of them from southeastern Turkey, hidden in the truck that
was about to be loaded onto a ship bound for Italy, according to
the news agency. (Turkey-Italy-Refugees)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu will
visit Washington on January 20 and hold talks with President Bill
Clinton on the Middle East peace process, the Prime Minister's
Office announced Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
This decision was reached earlier this evening between
Netanyahu and the U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
during their telephone conversation, the announcement said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu also briefed Albright over telephone on the budget
crisis the Israeli government faces right now, it added.
(Israel-Netanyahu-Clinton Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President
Yasser Arafat will travel to Washington on January 22 and hold
talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton on the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian news service, the Jerusalem Media and
Communication Center (JMCC), reported the PNA decision Saturday
evening.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, U.S. Middle East peace envoy Dennis
Ross will travel to the region to meet Arafat in the West Bank
city Bethlehem next Thursday as planned, JMCC said.
(Israel-Arafat-Clinton Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- Personal computer is in growing demand in the
United States and the trend towards cheaper PCs is expected to
continue in 1998, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. PC unit sales are expected to rise to 36.7 million in 1998
from 31.9 million last year, U.S. International Data Corp. said in
its latest report. (US-Computer) 
</P>
