<HEADLINE> Household-based Chinese Farmers Again Turn To Co-ops (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Cooperatives, which remind old
Chinese farmers of their unhappy times in the 1950 and '60s, are
emerging once again in rural areas. But the difference is that
farmers no longer see them as negative.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yumin of Laiyang City of east China's Shandong Province
was an eyewitness to the nationwide cooperative campaign at that
time. Now Wang, in his 60s, has set up a cooperative, the first in
his hometown.
</P>
<P>
"We were so naive then, taking it for granted that we could
purify our minds and live a better life just by working together,"
Wang said. "So we offered our means of production to the
collective in a hurry."
</P>
<P>
Wang admitted that he had been a staunch advocate of the
cooperative system, but that he now holds a different view.
</P>
<P>
China's rural reforms were actually initiated in 1978 by
farmers in Xiaogang Village of Fengyang County, Anhui Province,
when they risked prison to contract the collective's farmland in
secret on a household basis.
</P>
<P>
The late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping shared their idea and
spoke highly of the practice, which was later known as the
contract household responsibility system. Means of production,
including land, were returned to the farmers. The practice spread
around the country almost overnight, and helped the majority of
farmers rise from poverty within a few years.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in Wang's village of Zhujiatong have solved their food
problem by growing wheat and maize. Since the mid-1980s, the 150
families in the village have been growing vegetables as a way to
achieve prosperity.
</P>
<P>
But problems cropped up as individual households were
vulnerable to market risks and losses because of shoddy pesticides
and chemical fertilizer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
