<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Household-based Chinese Farmers Again Turn To Co-ops (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The rest of China's rural areas faced the same
problem. Economists attributed this to the contradiction of
small-scale production and big markets, explaining that
household-based agriculture made it difficult for farmers to have
timely and sufficient services in areas such as information,
technology, distribution and processing.
</P>
<P>
So farmers had to improve their methods of production and
management to adapt to a market economy.
</P>
<P>
In 1995 Wang presented his plan for a co-op which stipulated
that there would be no change in farmland ownership. Forty-three
households agreed to the plan, each contributing 500 yuan. The
vegetable co-op was responsible for providing high-quality means
of production at low prices, and for helping farmers sell their
products.
</P>
<P>
An increasing number of farmers have seen the benefits of
cooperatives. The city has established 413 co-ops covering nearly
70 percent of rural families.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, the trend toward cooperation has been
expanding in rural China. In Anhui Province, for example, farmers
have also begun to cooperate in conserving water, planting trees
in mountainous areas and other projects. Some farmers have formed
special technical associations to collect market information and
to seek larger market shares for their products.
</P>
<P>
The fact that Chinese farmers have begun to cooperate all over
again doesn't necessarily mean that they have had enough of the
responsibility system. Farmers say they still like the system but
just want to improve it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
