<HEADLINE> China Setting Up First Trading Market of Regenerated Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, January 4 (Xinhua) -- China has established its first
state-level trading market of regenerated resources in Tianjin,
the largest industrial port city of north China.
</P>
<P>
It symbolizes that China has entered a new stage in the aspect
of retrieving and utilizing regenerated resources, said well-known
economist Wu Xiang, who was former deputy head of the Rural
Development Research Center of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the market is financed by the China
General Supply and Marketing Cooperative and the Tianjin Municipal
Government. The China Regenerated Resources Corporation and the
Tianjin Municipal Supply and Marketing Cooperative are responsible
for its operation.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the market has been listed as a major project
in the field.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin is a center for collecting and distributing discarded
and used materials in north China. So far, it has 14 state-level
markets in operation.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the regenerated resources market will take
eight years to finish and will be carried out in three stages,
with the first stage completed last year.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2005 will chalk up 5.66 billion yuan worth of
business deals, including 1.66 billion yuan (200 million
U.S. dollars) worth of international business deals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
