<HEADLINE> Clinton to Propose Medicare Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton's
next budget is expected to include proposals to expand Medicare to
offer benefits to people under age 65 and restore food stamp
benefits that legal immigrants lost in the 1996 welfare reform,
according to news reports.
</P>
<P>
The Medicare proposal would allow people between 62 and 64 to
pay up to 400 dollars a month for health coverage, according to
The Washington Post and The Wall Street Journal. That would mark
the first time that people under 65 could obtain coverage in the
three-decade history of Medicare -- the federal health insurance
program covering about 40 millions of elderly and disabled
Americans.
</P>
<P>
The plan would enable people who often cannot afford private
insurance a chance to obtain coverage and repay the fees through a
surcharge after they reach age 65.
</P>
<P>
The food stamp proposal would restore benefits lost through the
1996 welfare overhaul by legal immigrants who are not yet
citizens.
</P>
<P>
The administration is not yet sure whether the restored
benefits should apply to all legal immigrants or only those in the
country when the bill became law last August.
</P>
<P>
Both plans will be part of Clinton's fiscal 1999 budget to be
formally unveiled next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
