<HEADLINE> U.S. Auto Sales Expected to Remain Steady </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. auto sales are expected to
top 15 million units for the fourth straight year in 1997, local
newspaper Investor's Business Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Given high consumer confidence, strong employment and growing
income, analysts see 1998 as another good year for auto makers.
</P>
<P>
Auto sales in 1998 may reach 15.3 million units, the paper
quoted Chrysler economist Van Bussman as saying. The prediction
was agreed by many others who believe that U.S. demand for autos
will stay strong.
</P>
<P>
Car sales in millions of units are projected 7.91 for 1998,
7.93 for 1999 and 8.07 for 2000 and trucks sales in million of
units are forecast 6.58 for 1998, 6.6 for 1999 and 6.77 for 2000,
according to a research unit of Federal Reserve bank of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
Light trucks' share of U.S. auto market grew to 44 percent in
1997 from some 25 percent in the early 80s.
</P>
<P>
Analysts see new truck products to continue improving U.S. auto
competitiveness as the Big Three, namely GM, Chrysler and Ford
have an advantage in quality and other consumer concerns.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts predict that U.S. auto makers may see
challenges from Japan and difficulties to further penetrate into
other Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
A depreciating Yen is to put Japanese makers in a good position
to increase their U.S. market share especially of compact cars.
</P>
<P>
Financial turmoil in Asia has already stalled U.S. auto exports
to countries such as Thailand and Malaysia considered the fastest
growing markets until recently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
