<HEADLINE> U.S. Market Sees More Less-Costly Computers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Personal computer is in
growing demand in the United States and the trend towards cheaper
PCs is expected to continue in 1998, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. PC unit sales are expected to rise to 36.7 million in 1998
from 31.9 million last year, U.S. International Data Corp. said in
its latest report.
</P>
<P>
By 2001, sales may hit close to 50 million, it added.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from other sources show that household PC
penetration in the U.S. may grow from 38.2 percent in 1997 to 40.3
percent this year and 47.8 percent in 2001.
</P>
<P>
One of the big stories in the U.S. technology market last year
was that over 30 percent of PCs were selling for under 1,000 U.S.
dollars per unit, as a result of the market expansion strategy.
</P>
<P>
The hot-selling sub-$1,000 PCs are to give up to sub-$800
models in 1998, market watchers predicted.
</P>
<P>
PC giant Hewlett-Packard Co. is leading the way to change the
strategy by introducing a $799 PC which uses a 200-megahertz Intel
chip, local newspaper Investor's Business Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
With profit margins narrowing under the price competition, more
consolidation is expected to occur among market players and it is
easier for the big ones to survive, analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
