<HEADLINE> Netanyahu, Clinton to Meet in Late January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu will visit Washington on January 20 and hold
talks with President Bill Clinton on the Middle East peace
process, the Prime Minister's Office announced Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
This decision was reached earlier this evening between
Netanyahu and the U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
during their telephone conversation, the announcement said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu also briefed Albright over telephone on the budget
crisis the Israeli government faces right now, it added.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told Albright that the 1998 state budget is
scheduled to go through the second and the third readings in the
Knesset (parliament) on Monday and after that he will travel to
Washington for talks with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset was originally scheduled to vote on the 1998 state
budget Thursday night, but the voting was postponed again after
Foreign Minister David Levy said in the same day that his Gesher
party will vote against it.
</P>
<P>
Levy lashed out at the government's socio-economic policy,
saying that the promises Netanyahu made to him last summer to aid
the poor and low-waged are ignored in the proposed budget.
</P>
<P>
He also criticized the government's foreign policy and doubted
it will agree on further troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Levy, who also threatened to resign on Thursday, will not
attend the weekly cabinet meeting on Sunday, his party sources
said. The Gesher party now holds five seats in the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said on Thursday that he will not let Levy resign,
because the government will collapse without Levy and his
party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
