<HEADLINE> U.S. Military to End Hay Airlift to New Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Six U.S. C-130 cargo planes
are ending an emergency airlift of hay to cattle and sheep that
were stranded in a severe snowstorm in southeast New Mexico as
ranchers can reach their herds now, local media reports said.
</P>
<P>
The New Mexico Department of Public Safety said that the
whether was improving and many ranchers could get out to their
herds.
</P>
<P>
The department said about 460 tons of hay would have been
dropped to the animals by C- 130 planes from Air National Guard
bases in Oklahoma, Texas, Wyoming, Minnesota and Idaho.
</P>
<P>
The Farm Services Agency offices from the U. S. Department of
Agriculture estimated that at least 5,000 animals have been killed
by severe cold and heavy snowstorms since Christmas Eve, and New
Mexican officials feared that about 180,000 more are at risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
